, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 20, 1999 || Clemson || 31\u201321 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 18, 2000 || Clemson || 16\u201314 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 17, 2001 || Carolina || 20\u201315 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 23, 2002 || Clemson || 27\u201320 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 22, 2003 || Clemson || 63\u201317 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 20, 2004 || Clemson || 29\u20137 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 19, 2005 || Clemson || 13\u20139 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 25, 2006 || Carolina || 31\u201328 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 24, 2007 || Clemson || 23\u201321 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 29, 2008 || Clemson || 31\u201314 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 28, 2009 || Carolina || 34\u201317 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 27, 2010 || Carolina || 29\u20137 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 26, 2011 || Carolina || 34\u201313 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 24, 2012 || Carolina || 27\u201317 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\"\n| November 30, 2013 || Carolina || 31\u201317 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 29, 2014 || Clemson || 35\u201317 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 28, 2015 || Clemson || 37\u201332 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 26, 2016 || Clemson || 56\u20137 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 25, 2017 || Clemson || 34\u201310 || Columbia, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 24, 2018 || Clemson || 56\u201335 || Clemson, SC\n|- style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\"\n| November 30, 2019 || Clemson || 38\u20133 || Columbia, SC\n|}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Baseball==\nIn baseball, Clemson leads the series overall 181\u2013141\u20132. The teams previously met four times during the regular season, with two games scheduled at each home field. Two of the games were played on Saturday and Sunday, and then later in the season 2 games were played during the mid-week, usually on Wednesday. Since 2010, the teams have competed against each other over the course of a single weekend: once on each home field and once at a neutral site. [[Fluor Field at the West End]] (2010, 2011, 2013-2019) in [[Greenville, SC]] and Riley Park (2012) in [[Charleston, SC]] have served as the host sites. The other instances where the teams met in neutral site games were the [[2002 College World Series]] and the [[2010 College World Series]], both times at [[Rosenblatt Stadium]] in [[Omaha, NE]]. Both schools are perennially considered to be among the top programs in the country, giving the rivalry a prominent spot in college baseball beyond the state of South Carolina.  SEBaseball.com's Mark Etheridge has called it \"college baseball's most heated rivalry,\"<ref name=etheridgerivalry>{{cite web|last=Etheridge |first=Mark |title=Nine Innings: Finishing Second or Next to Last |url=http://sebaseball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1369883 |work=SEBaseball.com |accessdate=May 29, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009213253/https://sebaseball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1369883 |archivedate=October 9, 2014 |date=May 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> and Baseball America's Aaron Fitt has called it \"far and away the most compelling rivalry college baseball has to offer.\"<ref name=fittrivalry>{{cite web|last=Fitt |first=Aaron |title=Weekend Preview: South Carolina, Clemson Get Together Again |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/college/weekend-preview/2012/2613047.html |work=BaseballAmerica.com |accessdate=May 29, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304162029/http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/college/weekend-preview/2012/2613047.html |archivedate=March 4, 2012 |date=March 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n===Recent series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size: 95%;\"\n!colspan=5|2020 Series\n!rowspan=2|All-Time Series\n|-\n!Date\n!Location\n!Winner\n!Score\n!Attendance\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | February 28, 2020\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | {{colored link|white|Founders Park}} \u2022 Columbia, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 7-1\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 8,242\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" rowspan=3 | Clemson<br />181\u2013141\u20132\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | February 29, 2020\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | {{colored link|white|Segra Park}} \u2022 Columbia, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | South Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 8-5\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 8,986 \n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | March 1, 2020\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | {{colored link|white|Doug Kingsmore Stadium}} \u2022 Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 5-2\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 5,655\n|}\n\n===College World Series in the 21st Century===\nThe rivalry has taken a deeper hold in the 2000s and 2010s, as twice in the century the two teams battled, coincidentally in the semifinals both times, with the Tigers being 2\u20130 and needing only one win to advance to the championship, and the Gamecocks losing the first game and having to win twice to reach the finals out of the double elimination [[repechage]] round in both situations.\n\n'''2002'''<br>\nLeading up to the [[2002 College World Series|2002 semifinals]], Clemson had already won three out of four regular season games against Carolina.  The Gamecocks beat their rivals soundly, 12\u20134, and then beat the Tigers again, 10\u20132, the following day to advance to the national championship game. The Gamecocks fell to Texas 12\u20136 in the championship game, the last under the format where a one-game final was played.<ref>[http://www.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/scar/sports/m-basebl/auto_pdf/07-media-guide South Carolina Baseball Media Guide 2007], p. 111.</ref>\n\n'''2010'''<br>\nEight years later, in what has been called [[2010 College World Series|The Last Bat at Rosenblatt]], an identical situation leading to the series began.  Clemson had taken both on-campus games from South Carolina in the regular season, including a lopsided 19\u20136 victory in the rubber match, played before over 8,000 fans at [[Carolina Stadium]] in Columbia, but had lost in the \"neutral site\" game.  The Gamecocks had just come off a 12-inning win against the [[Oklahoma Sooners]] less than 24 hours before, while the Tigers had two days of rest.  However, fatigue was not a factor as the Gamecocks won the first game, 5\u20131, on a dominating complete game pitching performance by reliever Michael Roth, who had not started a game in more than a year.  Carolina won the second game the following day, 4\u20133, to advance to the championship series against [[2010 UCLA Bruins baseball team|UCLA]], who they defeated, 7\u20131 (Game 1) and 2\u20131 (Game 2) to win the [[NCAA Division I Baseball Championship]].  South Carolina went on to win the National Championship again against Florida in 2011 and finished \"runner-up\" to Arizona in 2012.\n\n==Other varsity sports==\n\n===Men's teams===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size: 95%;\"\n!rowspan=2|Sport\n!colspan=5|Last Matchup\n!colspan=2|All-Time Series\n|-\n!Date\n!Location\n!Winner\n!Score\n!Attendance\n!Leader\n!Record\n|-\n|Basketball\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | December 15, 2019\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | [[Littlejohn Coliseum|<span style=\"color:white;\">Littlejohn Coliseum</span>]] \u2022 Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 67-54\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 6,394\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 91\u201379\n|-\n|Soccer\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | August 30, 2019\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | [[Riggs Field|<span style=\"color:white;\">Riggs Field</span>]] \u2022 Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 4\u20131\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | ---\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 30\u201317\u20131\n|-\n|Tennis\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | February 15, 2019\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina Tennis Center \u2022 Columbia, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 4\u20133\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 68\u201340\u20132\n|-\n|}\n*Carolina does not sponsor Men's Cross Country.\n*Golf and Track & Field teams do not compete head-to-head.\n\n===Women's teams===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size: 95%;\"\n!rowspan=2|Sport\n!colspan=5|Last Matchup\n!colspan=2|All-Time Series\n|-\n!Date\n!Location\n!Winner\n!Score\n!Attendance\n!Leader\n!Record\n|-\n|Basketball\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | November 24, 2019\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | [[Littlejohn Coliseum|<span style=\"color:white;\">Littlejohn Coliseum</span>]] \u2022 Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 84\u201348\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 2,830\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 33\u201332\n|-\n|Soccer\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | September 15, 2019\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | [[Riggs Field|<span style=\"color:white;\">Riggs Field</span>]] \u2022 Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 1\u20130\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 1,625\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | Clemson \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}}\" | 14\u201311\u20131\n|-\n|Tennis\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | January 30, 2020\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina Tennis Center \u2022 Columbia, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 6\u20131\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" |  29\u201327\n|-\n|Volleyball\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | September 12, 2019\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Jervey Athletic Center * Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 3\u20132\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 41\u201324\n|}\n*Carolina does not sponsor Rowing.\n*Clemson does not sponsor Equestrian or Lacrosse.  Clemson will begin playing softball in 2020. Carolina won the only meeting of the Softball teams, in 1979.\n*Cross Country, Golf, and Track & Field teams do not compete head-to-head.\n\n===Discontinued sports===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size: 95%;\"\n!rowspan=2|Sport\n!colspan=5|Final Matchup\n!colspan=2|All-Time Series\n|-\n!Date\n!Location\n!Winner\n!Score\n!Attendance\n!Leader\n!Record\n|-\n|Men's Swimming & Diving\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | October 29, 2011\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Westside Aquatic Center \u2022 Greenville, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 162\u2013137\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 35\u201313\n|-\n|Women's Swimming & Diving\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | October 29, 2011\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Westside Aquatic Center \u2022 Greenville, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 191\u2013108\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 22\u201314\n|-\n|Women's Diving\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | November 9, 2016\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | McHugh Natatorium \u2022 Clemson, SC\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 28\u201310\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | \n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | Carolina\n|style=\"{{NCAA color cell|South Carolina Gamecocks}}\" | 4\u20131\n|}\n*Clemson discontinued men's swimming & diving and women's swimming after the 2011\u20132012 season.\n*Clemson sponsored women's diving as a standalone sport from the 2012\u20132013 season until the 2016\u20132017 season, when it was discontinued.\n\n==Blood drive==\n{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 28em; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n| '''Series Originated'''\n| 1985\n|-\n| '''Overall Record'''\n| Carolina leads, 18-17\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|<hr />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"width:14em\" | [[File:Usc-gamecocks-text-logo.gif|150px|South Carolina logo]]\n| align=\"center\" style=\"width:14em\" | [[File:Clemson University Wordmark.svg|150px|Clemson logo]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''Carolina (18)'''<br />1987 1993 1998 1999<br />2001 2002 2003 2004<br />2005 2008 2009 2010<br />2011 2012 2013 2014<br />2015 2017\n| align=\"center\" | '''Clemson (17)'''<br />1985 1986 1988 1989<br />1990 1991 1992 1994<br />1995 1996 1997 2000<br />2006 2007 2016 2018<br />2019\n|-\n| align=center colspan=\"2\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"|\n|}\nThe rivalry extends beyond sports to the annual [[blood donation|blood drive]] between the two schools. Students, faculty and fans from the schools band together in an effort to collect blood before the holiday season when many are too busy to give blood. The drive is held from Monday through Friday the week before the football matchup. The University of South Carolina and Clemson University wrapped up their 35th annual blood drive in 2019, resulting in the second consecutive win for Clemson. Carolina now holds an 18\u201317 lead in the yearly competition.\n\nThe 2019 Carolina-Clemson Blood Drive took place on both campuses Nov 18\u201322 with students, staff, faculty and fans showing support for their favorite team by donating blood. This year's event resulted in 4,549 donors presenting to give blood. Carolina support totaled 2,108 donors, while Clemson support totaled 2,441 donors. The blood drive is sponsored by The Blood Connection and [[American Red Cross]] at the University of South Carolina with the help of the University of South Carolina Fraternity and Sorority Council<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sa.sc.edu/fsl/carolina-clemson-blood-drive/|title=Fraternity and Sorority Life - Fraternity and Sorority Life - University of South Carolina|website=www.sa.sc.edu}}</ref> in addition to the Men's Rugby team and the Gamma Lambda chapter of the [[Alpha Phi Omega]] national service fraternity at Clemson, and the two schools have collected 153,320 pints of blood over the past thirty five years. Everyone who gives blood receives a free shirt, with the graphic on the back usually featuring a Tiger and Gamecock together and a statement explaining that even though the competition is part of the rivalry, both schools share the common ground of giving blood. It is currently the largest collegiate blood drive in the country.\n\n==Certified SC Grown Palmetto Series==\nOn August 4, 2015, leaders from the South Carolina Department of Agriculture, Clemson University, and the University of South Carolina gathered at the South Carolina State House to announce the launch of the Certified SC Grown Palmetto Series, in which the Tigers and Gamecocks will compete for the Palmetto Series trophy based primarily on head to head athletic competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clemsontigers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=28500&ATCLID=210250309&SPID=103723&SPSID=658250|title=Certified SC Grown Palmetto Series Announced|access-date=August 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923222214/http://www.clemsontigers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=28500&ATCLID=210250309&SPID=103723&SPSID=658250|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe following 13 sports will count toward the series: baseball, men's basketball, women's basketball, women's cross country, women's diving, football, men's golf, women's golf, men's soccer, women's soccer, men's tennis, women's tennis, and volleyball. These are all sports that either compete head to head or will face each other in the same tournament or meet. The winning team in each sport (including postseason) earns one point, while a half a point will be awarded if the teams evenly split a series throughout the year (example, if Carolina baseball were to win 2 of 3 from Clemson in the regular season, but Clemson later wins 2 of 3 in postseason play, both teams would be awarded half a point each for splitting their meetings). In the case of a tie in the 2015\u20132016 year, the winner of the schools' annual food drive and the average student athlete GPA will be used for tie breaker. After the 2015\u20132016 year, the previous year's winner will retain the Palmetto Series trophy in the event of a tie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://palmettoseries.com/details/|title=Certified SC Grown - Palmetto Series|website=palmettoseries.com}}</ref>\n\nOn July 7, 2016, the University of South Carolina was named winner of the inaugural Palmetto Series with a score of 10\u20135.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://palmettoseries.com/2016/07/07/519/|title=Palmetto Series|last=|first=|date=July 7, 2016|website=Palmetto Series|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2017, Carolina won the Palmetto Series for the second straight year with a score of 8\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://palmettoseries.com/2017/07/06/gamecocks-win-certified-sc-grown-palmetto-series-second-year-in-a-row/|title=Certified SC Grown - Palmetto Series|website=palmettoseries.com}}</ref>\n\nSouth Carolina won the Palmetto Series for the third consecutive year in 2018 by a score of 8\u20137.\n\nSouth Carolina won the Palmetto Series for the fourth consecutive year in 2019 by a score of 9.5\u20134.5. Clemson has yet to win a Palmetto Series trophy.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==See also== \n* [[List of NCAA college football rivalry games]]\n* [[List of most-played college football series in NCAA Division I]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book | last = Ball | first = William Watts | title = The State That Forgot; South Carolina's Surrender to Democracy | year = 1932 | publisher = The Bobbs-Merrill Company | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Cooper | first = William | title = The Conservative Regime: South Carolina, 1877\u20131890 | year = 2005 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | isbn = 1-57003-597-0 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book | first = Walter B. | last = Edgar | title = South Carolina:  A History | year = 1998 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | ref = harv}}\n* {{Citation | first = Daniel Walker | last = Hollis | title = University of South Carolina | year = 1951 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | volume = I | ref = harv}}\n* {{Citation | first = Daniel Walker | last = Hollis | title = University of South Carolina | year = 1956 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | volume = II | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book | first = Henry H. | last = Lesesne | title = A History of the University of South Carolina, 1940\u20132000 | year = 2001 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://thepalmettobowl.com/ The Palmetto Bowl]\n\n{{Clemson University}}\n{{University of South Carolina}}\n{{Navboxes\n| list =\n{{Clemson Tigers football navbox}}\n{{Clemson Tigers men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Clemson Tigers baseball navbox}}\n{{Clemson Tigers softball navbox}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks football navbox}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball navbox}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks baseball navbox}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks men's soccer navbox}}\n{{Atlantic Coast Conference rivalry navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football rivalry navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clemson-South Carolina rivalry}}\n[[Category:College sports rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College baseball rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College basketball rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College football rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College soccer rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:Clemson Tigers]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clemson%E2%80%93South_Carolina_rivalry"}
{"title_page": "Jacob's Ladder (1990 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1990 film directed by Adrian Lyne}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Jacob's Ladder\n| image = Jacobsladderposter.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Adrian Lyne]]\n| producer = [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]\n| writer = [[Bruce Joel Rubin]]\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tim Robbins]]\n* [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]]\n* [[Danny Aiello]]\n}}\n| music = [[Maurice Jarre]]\n| cinematography = [[Jeffrey L. Kimball]]\n| editing = [[Tom Rolf]]\n| studio = [[Carolco Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[TriStar Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|1990|11|02}}\n| runtime = 113 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 113:02--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/jacobs-ladder-1970-3 | title=''Jacob's Ladder'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 6, 1990 | accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $25 million<ref name=nyt>Time Golden, [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/28/arts/film-up-jacob-s-ladder-and-into-the-hell-of-a-veteran-s-psyche.html Up 'Jacob's Ladder' And Into the Hell Of a Veteran's Psyche], ''The New York Times'', October 28, 1990.</ref>\n| gross = $26.1 million<ref name=mojo>{{mojo title|jacobsladder|Jacob's Ladder}}.</ref>\n}}\n'''''Jacob's Ladder''''' is a 1990 American [[psychological horror]] film directed by [[Adrian Lyne]], produced by [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]], written by [[Bruce Joel Rubin]], and starring [[Tim Robbins]], [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]], and [[Danny Aiello]]. The film's protagonist, Jacob, is a [[Vietnam veteran]] whose experiences prior to and during the war result in strange, fragmentary visions and bizarre hallucinations that continue to haunt him. As his ordeal worsens, Jacob desperately attempts to figure out the truth.\n\n''Jacob's Ladder'' was made by [[Carolco Pictures]] ten years after being written by Rubin. Though only moderately successful upon release, the film garnered a [[Cult film|cult following]] and its plot and special effects became a source of influence for various other works such as the horror video game  ''[[Silent Hill]]''. A remake, also titled ''[[Jacob's Ladder (2019 film)|Jacob's Ladder]]'', was released in 2019.\n\n==Plot==\nOn October 6, 1971, an American [[infantryman]], Jacob Singer, is with the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Air Cavalry Division]], deployed in a village in Vietnam's [[Mekong Delta]], when his close-knit unit comes under sudden attack. As many of Jacob's comrades are killed or wounded, others exhibit abnormal behavior with some suffering [[catatonia]], convulsions, and seizures. Jacob flees into the jungle, only to be stabbed with a [[bayonet]] by an unseen assailant.\n\nJacob awakens in the [[New York City Subway]], where, after glimpsing what he believes to be a tentacle protruding from a sleeping homeless person, an inexplicably locked subway station exit results in him almost being hit by a train. The year is 1975, he works as a postal clerk, and lives in a rundown apartment in [[Brooklyn]] with his girlfriend, Jezebel. Jacob misses his old family and experiences visions of them, especially the youngest of his sons, Gabe, who had died in an accident before the war. Jacob is increasingly beset by disturbing experiences and apparitions, including glimpses of faceless vibrating figures, and narrowly escapes being run over by a pursuing car. He attempts to contact his regular doctor at the local [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|VA hospital]], but after first being told that there is no record of him ever being a patient there, Jacob is told that his doctor has died in a car explosion.\n\nAt a party thrown by friends, a [[psychic]] reads Jacob's palm and tells him that he is already dead, which Jacob dismisses as a joke. After declining to dance with her, he appears to witness an enormous tentacled creature having sex with and then impaling Jezzie through the mouth before he collapses. At home, Jacob experiences a dangerous fever, which Jezzie attempts to bring down with a painful ice bath. Jacob briefly wakes up in another reality where he lives with his wife and sons, including a still-alive Gabe. First-person perspective scenes of apparent [[Flashback (psychology)|flashbacks]] to his time in Vietnam show Jacob, badly wounded, being discovered by American soldiers before being evacuated under fire in a helicopter.\n\nOne of Jacob's former platoon mates, Paul, contacts him to reveal he is suffering from similar experiences, but is soon afterwards killed when his car explodes. Commiserating after the funeral, other surviving members of the platoon confess that they have all been experiencing horrifying hallucinations. Believing that they are suffering the effects of a military experiment performed on them without their knowledge or consent, they hire a lawyer to investigate. However the lawyer quits the case after reading military files documenting that the soldiers were never in combat and were discharged for psychological reasons. Jacob's comrades soon back down while Jacob suspects they have been threatened into doing so. He is abducted by suited men who try to intimidate him. Jacob fights them and escapes but is injured and nearly paralyzed in the process. He is taken to a nightmarish hospital, where he is told he has been killed and this is home, but his [[chiropractor]] friend Louis comes to his rescue and heals him. Louis quotes the 14th-century [[Christian mysticism|Christian mystic]], [[Meister Eckhart]]:\n\n<blockquote>Eckhart saw [[Hell]] too. He said: \"The only thing that burns in Hell is the part of you that won't let go of life, your memories, your attachments. They burn them all away. But they're not punishing you\", he said. \"They're freeing your soul. So, if you're frightened of dying and ... you're holding on, you'll see [[devil]]s tearing your life away. But if you've made your peace, then the devils are really [[angel]]s, freeing you from the earth.\"</blockquote>\n\nJacob is approached by a distressed man who was seen treating his wound in a [[Medical evacuation|medevac]] helicopter and who also dragged him away from Paul's burning car. Introducing himself as Michael Newman, he tells a story of having been a chemist with [[Chemical Corps|the Army's chemical warfare division]] where he designed a drug he called the Ladder, which massively increased aggression. Michael claims that, to test the drug's effectiveness, a dose was secretly given to Jacob's unit before the battle, causing some of them to turn on each other in a homicidal frenzy. Michael's story triggers a vision of Jacob's wounding in Vietnam, which shows his attacker as a fellow American soldier. Jacob returns to his family's home, where he finds Gabe, who takes him by the hand and leads him up the staircase into a bright light. The scene turns to a [[triage]] tent in 1971 as military doctors declare Jacob dead. The doctor notes that Jacob had put up a tremendous fight to stay alive, but looked peaceful in death.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as Jacob \"Professor\" Singer\n* [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]] as Jezebel \"Jezzie\" Pipkin\n* [[Danny Aiello]] as Louis \"Louie\" Denardo\n* [[Matt Craven]] as Michael Newman\n* [[Pruitt Taylor Vince]] as Paul Gruneger\n* [[Jason Alexander]] as Mr. Geary, the lawyer\n* [[Patricia Kalember]] as Sarah\n* [[Eriq La Salle]] as Frank\n* [[Ving Rhames]] as George\n* [[Brian Tarantina]] as Doug\n* Anthony Alessandro as Rod\n* [[Brent Hinkley]] as Jerry\n* [[S. Epatha Merkerson]] as Elsa\n* [[Kyle Gass]] as Tony\n* [[Lewis Black]] as Jacob's doctor\n* [[Perry Lang]] as Jacob's assailant\n* [[Macaulay Culkin]] (uncredited) as Gabe Singer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n{{quote box|quote=The horror of the movie would be in the revelation that hope is hell's final torment, that life is a dream that ends over and over with the final truth: that life was never real, that we are all creatures trapped in eternal suffering and damnation.|source=\u2013[[Bruce Joel Rubin]]<ref>Paul Meehan, ''Horror Noir: Where Cinema's Dark Sisters Meet'', McFarland, 2011 (p.259).</ref>|width=30%}}\n\nThe film's title refers to the Biblical story of [[Jacob's Ladder]], or the dream of a meeting place between [[Heaven]] and Earth ([[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 28:12). Its little-known alternative title is ''Dante's Inferno'', in a reference to ''[[Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]]'' by [[Dante Alighieri]].<ref>John Flowers, Paul Frizler, ''Psychotherapists on Film, 1899-1999: A Worldwide Guide to Over 5000 Films, Volume 1'', McFarland, 2004 (p.309).</ref><ref>Pamela Jaye Smith, ''Inner Drives'', Michael Wiese Productions, 2005 (p.217).</ref><ref>Eric G. Wilson, ''Secret Cinema: Gnostic Vision in Film'', Bloomsbury, 2006 (p.123).</ref> Screenwriter and co-producer [[Bruce Joel Rubin]] perceived the film as a modern interpretation of the ''[[Bardo Thodol|Liberation Through Hearing During the Intermediate State]]'', the [[Tibet]]an Book of the Dead.<ref name=\"st\">{{cite news | title = Adrian Lyne Met A Metaphysical Challenge | first = John | last = Hartl | url = http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19901101&slug=1101695 | work = [[The Seattle Times]] | date = November 1, 1990 | accessdate = February 6, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = FILM; Up 'Jacob's Ladder' And Into the Hell Of a Veteran's Psyche | first = Tim | last = Golden | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/28/arts/film-up-jacob-s-ladder-and-into-the-hell-of-a-veteran-s-psyche.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = October 28, 1990 | accessdate = October 22, 2007 }}</ref> Rubin said: \"The inspiration in a sense is my entire spiritual upbringing. Once you have a [[Buddhist meditation|meditative life]] you start to see that the world is really far different than what it appears to be. What appears to be finite is really couched in the infinite, and the infinite imbues everything in our lives.\"<ref>''Tricycle: The Buddhist Review - Volume 1'', Buddhist Ray, 1991 (p.77).</ref> Before writing his scripts for ''Jacob's Ladder'' and ''[[Ghost (1990 film)|Ghost]]'', which too was released in 1990, the Jewish-born Rubin spent two years in a [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan Buddhist]] monastery in Nepal;<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>Carrol Lee Fry, ''Cinema of the Occult: New Age, Satanism, Wicca, and Spiritualism in Film'', Associated University Presse, 2008 (p.77).</ref> previously, he has also written [[afterlife]]-themed ''[[Brainstorm (1983 film)|Brainstorm]]'' and ''[[Deadly Friend]]''.\n\nRubin's work on ''Jacob's Ladder'' began in 1980, sparked by his nightmare in which he dreamt about being trapped in a subway. For several years, Rubin tried to sell the script, without success; [[Thom Mount]] of [[Universal Pictures]] said he \"loved it, but it was not for his studio\". Directors [[Michael Apted]], [[Sidney Lumet]] and [[Ridley Scott]] all expressed an interest in making the film, but still no major studio was ready to invest in Rubin's \"too [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]]\" stories as \"Hollywood does not make [[List of ghost films|ghost movies]]\". Eventually, after ''Deadly Friend'' was filmed by [[Wes Craven]] in 1986, Rubin's screenplays for both ''Jacob's Ladder'' and ''Ghost'' were picked by [[Paramount Pictures]].<ref name=\"st\" /> In 1988,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> [[Adrian Lyne]], who described Rubin's work as \"certainly one of the best scripts I've ever read\", decided then to direct it instead of an adaptation of ''[[The Bonfire of the Vanities]]'' as he had originally planned (incidentally, [[Tom Hanks]], an actor originally considered by Lyne for the role of Jacob, ended up starring in ''Bonfire''). The ownership and policy changes at Paramount resulted in the cancellation of the project; the executives had doubts about the film's ending and the scenes taking place in Vietnam. The [[independent film]] studio [[Carolco Pictures]] decided to take over the production of ''Jacob's Ladder'', giving Lyne a greater creative control<ref name=\"st\" /> and a budget of $25 million.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Rubin became the film's co-producer, along with [[Mario Kassar]], [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]] and [[Andrew G. Vajna]].\n\n{{quote box|quote=I can see why people didn't want to make it for so long. It reads like a novel, and it's very intimidating because it's written so descriptively. Bruce had these very literal images of heaven and hell that I didn't know how to bring off. How do you introduce a character with horns?|source=\u2013[[Adrian Lyne]]<ref name=st/>|width=30%}}\n\nLyne, who downplayed Rubin's \"intimidating\" [[Old Testament]] themes,<ref name=\"after\">Tom Ruffles, ''Ghost Images: Cinema of the Afterlife'', McFarland, 2004 (p.192).</ref> said that he prepared for making the film by watching \"endless\" documentary films about the war in Vietnam and reading \"countless\" chronicles of [[near-death experience]]s.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> The film's plot device of a long period of [[Time perception|subjective time]] passing in an instant has been explored by several authors. A particularly strong inspiration for both Rubin and Lyne was [[Robert Enrico]]'s 1962 short film ''[[An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge (film)|An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge]]'',<ref name=\"rubin\">Bruce Joel Rubin, ''Jacob's Ladder'', Applause Theatre & Cinema Books, 1990.</ref> one of Lyne's favourite movies,<ref name=\"st\" /> which was in turn based on [[Ambrose Bierce]]'s 1890 short story [[An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge|of the same title]].\n\nCast in the role of Jacob, [[Tim Robbins]] said the film presented for him \"a great opportunity to go in a different direction. I love doing comedy, but I know I can do other things as well.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /> The film's military advisor was Vietnam veteran Captain [[Dale Dye]],<ref>Almar Haflidason, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/10/15/dale_dye_2001_2_interview.shtml Dale Dye: Part 2 - Stop Whining at Me!], BBC, October 2003.</ref> who provided a five-day [[Recruit training|boot camp]] military training for the actors playing soldiers in the Vietnam storyline (including Robbins, [[Pruitt Taylor Vince]], [[Eriq La Salle]] and [[Ving Rhames]]). The war scenes were filmed in the [[Puerto Rico]] area of [[Vega Baja]], featuring the [[UH-1 Iroquois|UH-1]] helicopters provided by the [[Puerto Rico National Guard]].\n\nAll of the film's special effect sequences were filmed in camera, with no use of post production effects. In several scenes of ''Jacob's Ladder'', Lyne used a [[body horror]] technique in which an actor is recorded shaking his head around at a low [[frame rate]], resulting in horrifically fast motion when played back. In the Special Edition's commentary track, Lyne said he was inspired by the art of the painter [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]] when developing the effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.widerscreenings.com/jacobsladder.html |title=Jacob's Ladder |publisher=Widerscreenings.com |date=|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> In his screenplay, Rubin used traditional imagery of demons and hell. However, Lyne decided to use images similar to [[thalidomide]] deformities to achieve a greater shock effect.<ref name=\"rubin\" /> After many heated arguments,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Lyne managed to convert Rubin to his vision. Lyne and Rubin used the works of the artist [[H. R. Giger]] and the photographers [[Diane Arbus]] and [[Joel-Peter Witkin]] for inspiration; another influence came from the [[Brothers Quay]]'s 1986 [[stop motion]] short film ''[[Street of Crocodiles]]''.\n\n{{quote box|quote=Vietnam was really a means to an end. It was a plot device rather than something we were trying to make a huge issue of.|source=\u2013[[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]<ref name=nyt/>|width=30%}}\n\nIn the film, Jacob is told by Michael that the horrific events he experienced on his final day in Vietnam were the product of an experimental drug called \"the Ladder\", which was used on troops without their knowledge. At the end of the film, a message is displayed saying that reports of testing of BZ, [[NATO]] code for a [[deliriant]] and [[hallucinogen]] known as [[3-Quinuclidinyl benzilate|3-quinuclidinyl benzilate]], on U.S. soldiers during the Vietnam War were denied by the [[United States Department of Defense|Pentagon]]. Lyne said a part of the inspiration for this motif was [[Martin A. Lee]]'s book ''[[Acid Dreams: The CIA, LSD and Sixties Rebellion]]'', but noted that \"nothing in the book suggests that the drug BZ \u2014 a super-hallucinogen that has a tendency to elicit [[Mania|maniac behavior]] \u2014 was used on U.S. troops.\"<ref name=\"st\" />\n\nAccording to Lyne's audio commentary, [[test screening]]s indicated that the initial version of the film was overwhelming for the audience. In response, about 20 minutes of disturbing scenes, mostly from the last third of the film, were removed from the final cut.\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical release===\n''Jacob's Ladder'' opened on November 2, 1990, distributed by [[TriStar Pictures]]. ''Jacob's Ladder: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' with the music by [[Maurice Jarre]] was released by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|author=Maurice Jarre |url=https://www.amazon.com/Jacobs-Ladder-Original-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B0000014RW |title=Jacob's Ladder: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref> Rubin's companion book, released by [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Applause Theater Book Publishers]] on the same day as the film,<ref name=\"st\" /> features a final draft of the screenplay, including the [[deleted scene]]s, and his essay on making of the screenplay and the film.<ref name=\"rubin\" />\n\n===Home media===\nThe Special Edition [[DVD]] was released by [[Artisan Entertainment]] on July 14, 1998, containing three deleted scenes (\"Jezzie's Transformation\", \"The Antidote\" and \"The Train Station\") along with several other special features, such as audio commentary by Adrian Lyne and a 26-minute [[making-of]] documentary \"Building ''Jacob's Ladder''\".<ref name=\"dvd\" /> On September 14, 2010, the film was released on [[Blu-ray Disc]] by [[Lions Gate Entertainment]] and retains all of the special features of the DVD version, along with two [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]]s, omitting only a TV spot that came with the DVD.<ref name=\"ign\">R.L. Shaffer, [http://uk.ign.com/articles/2010/09/14/jacobs-ladder-blu-ray-review Jacob's Ladder Blu-ray Review], IGN, September 14, 2010,</ref><ref name=\"br\" />\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film took the number one spot at the weekend [[box office]] in North America, garnering ticket sales of $7.5 million from 1,052 screens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-11-05/entertainment/ca-3119_1_ticket-sales |title='Jacob's Ladder' Climbs to Top of Ticket Sales. - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=August 17, 2000 |accessdate=June 28, 2013 |first=Pat H. |last=Broeske}}</ref> However, the attendance dropped fast and its overall domestic box office result was only $26,118,851.<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\n===Critical reception===\nAccording to aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 72% approval rating based on 64 reviews, with an average rating of 6.57/10. The site's consensus reads: \"Even with its disorienting leaps of logic and structure, ''Jacob's Ladder'' is an engrossing, nerve-shattering experience\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jacobs_ladder/|title=Jacob's Ladder (1990)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C-\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' wrote that watching it left him \"reeling with turmoil and confusion, with feelings of sadness and despair,\" and called it a \"thoroughly painful and depressing experience \u2014 but, it must be said, one that has been powerfully written, directed and acted.\" He awarded the film three and a half out of a possible four stars.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19901102/REVIEWS/11020301/1023 | title = Jacob's Ladder | last = Ebert | first = Roger | date = November 2, 1990 | publisher = Rogerebert.suntimes.com | accessdate = April 16, 2010 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that this \"slick, riveting, viscerally scary film about what in other hands would be a decidedly unsalable subject, namely [[death]],\" is \"both quaint and devastating.\"<ref>Janet Maslin, [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE7D8143CF931A35752C1A966958260 Movie Review - Jacob s Ladder - Review/Film; It's Scary, Yes, and Death Has a Role], ''The New York Times'', November 2, 1990.</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Desson Thomson]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' felt disappointed with the film that is \"ultimately flat on its [[Surrealism|surrealistic]] face, the victim of too many fake-art sequences.\"<ref>Desson Howe, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/jacobsladderrhowe_a0b2b5.htm 'Jacob's Ladder' (R)], ''Washington Post'', November 2, 1990.</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that \"''Jacob's Ladder'' is so 'dark' it sucks Robbins right down with it. By the time Jacob is being strapped to a bed and wheeled down a hospital corridor strewn with bloody limbs, it's hard to care whether the [[Orwellian]] image is a hallucination or not. You just want out.\"<ref>Owen Gleiberman, [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318521,00.html Jacob's Ladder (1990)], EW.com, November 2, 1990.</ref> [[Kim Newman]] called the film \"effectively the blunt remake\" of ''[[Carnival of Souls]]''.<ref name=\"after\" />\n\nAccording to [[IGN]]'s review of the DVD release in 2004, \"After movies like ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Se7en]]'', it may not pack the same subtle horror for today's audiences it did when it was first released, but it's still a great film.\"<ref name=\"dvd\">Mike Drucker, [http://uk.ign.com/articles/2004/11/08/jacobs-ladder Jacob's Ladder: The living nightmare of a movie has a pretty decent DVD.], IGN, November 8, 2004.</ref> IGN's review of ''Jacob's Ladder''{{'}}s 2010 Blu-ray release called it \"an emotionally poignant, creepy horror masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"ign\" /> According to ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', ''Jacob's Ladder'' is \"a bizarrely cohesive hybrid of war movie, character study, [[art film]], and horror flick\" and \"the very act of watching the film is so emotionally draining that the viewer leaves the film feeling worked-in; the thought of repeat viewings is daunting yet insatiable.\"<ref name=\"br\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/jacobs-ladder/1807 |title=Jacob's Ladder <nowiki>&#124;</nowiki> DVD Review |magazine=Slant Magazine |date=September 14, 2010 |accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref> [[John Kenneth Muir]] called the film's nightmarish hospital scene \"one of the most terrifying moments in all of 1990s horror cinema.\" Muir further wrote: \"In its musings about death, about the end we all fear'', Jacob's Ladder'' proves a deeply affecting and meaningful motion picture. After a screening, you'll immediately want to hug the people you love and then go outside and breathe the fresh air, or otherwise affirm your very existence.\"<ref>John Kenneth Muir, ''Horror Films of the 1990s'', McFarland, 2011 (p.105).</ref>\n\nRubin's script was included on the list of \"Hollywood's ten best unproduced screenplays\" by ''American Film'' magazine in 1983.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In 1991, ''Jacob's Ladder'' was nominated at [[Horror Hall of Fame]] II for best horror film, losing to ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]''. The film was also featured in [[Bravo (U.S. TV channel)|Bravo]]'s 2004 documentary miniseries ''[[The 100 Scariest Movie Moments]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030070540/http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml |archivedate=October 30, 2007 |title=The 100 Scariest Movie Moments: 100 Scariest Moments in Movie History - Official Bravo TV Site |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref> and in the 2009 book ''[[1001 Movies You Must See Before You Die]]''. In 2013, the [[Jacob Burns Film Center]] projectionist Andrew Robinson chose it as his favourite scary movie.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.burnsfilmcenter.org/halloween-countdown-day-8-jacobs-ladder/ |title=Halloween Countdown \u2013 Day 8: Jacob's Ladder \u00bb Jacob Burns Film Center Blog |publisher=Blog.burnsfilmcenter.org |date=October 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 23, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728200336/http://blog.burnsfilmcenter.org/halloween-countdown-day-8-jacobs-ladder/ |archivedate=July 28, 2014  }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''Jacob's Ladder'' greatly inspired the horror  ''[[Silent Hill]]'',<ref>John Gaudiosi, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/johngaudiosi/2012/11/02/resident-evil-and-silent-hill-producer-samuel-hadida-talks-wolfenstein-and-onimusha-movies/ Resident Evil And Silent Hill Producer Samuel Hadida Talks Wolfenstein And Onimusha Movies],  Forbes, February 11, 2012.</ref> including the video games ''[[Silent Hill (video game)|Silent Hill]]'' (1999),<ref>Bernard Perron, ''Silent Hill: The Terror Engine'', University of Michigan Press, 2012 (p. 55-56).</ref> ''[[Silent Hill 2]]'' (2001),<ref>[http://uk.ign.com/articles/2001/08/17/interview-with-silent-hill-2s-artist-takayoshi-sato Interview with Silent Hill 2&#039,s Artist Takayoshi Sato], IGN, August 17, 2001.</ref> ''[[Silent Hill 3]]'' (2003),<ref>[http://uk.ign.com/articles/2002/06/12/silent-hill-3-interview Silent Hill 3 Interview], IGN, June 12, 2002</ref> ''[[Silent Hill 4: The Room]]'' (2004),<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/collective/A3066879| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227080553/http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/collective/A3066879| archivedate = December 27, 2007| title = Silent Hill 4: The Room| author = Daniel Etherington| work = [[bbc.co.uk]]| date = October 1, 2004| accessdate = June 9, 2007}}</ref> and ''[[Silent Hill: Homecoming]]'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|last=Grayson |first=Vincent |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/52765/silent-hill-5-interview-jasons |title=Silent Hill 5 Interview: Jason's Philosophy, Jacob's Ladder, and Pyramid Head |publisher=Shacknews.com |date=|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> as well as the series' 2006 [[Silent Hill (film)|film adaptation]] by [[Christophe Gans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/219 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328090017/http://bloody-disgusting.com/interview/219 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 28, 2016 |title=Interview Silent Hill: Director Christophe Gans |publisher=Bloody Disgusting |accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> The film's influence on their works was also recognised by [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]], writer of the 2011 TV series ''[[American Horror Story: Asylum]]'',<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/03/jessica-lange-the-name-game_n_2402373.html Jessica Lange Sings 'The Name Game': 'American Horror Story: Asylum' Goes Musical], HUFFPOST TV, March 1, 2013</ref> and by [[Shinji Mikami]], director of the 2014 video game ''[[The Evil Within]]''.<ref name=ign2>Lucy O'Brien, [http://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/05/06/the-movie-every-survival-horror-fan-should-watch \"Am I dying, Louie?\"], IGN, May 16, 2013.</ref> [[Kim Manners]] prepared for directing ''[[The X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Grotesque (The X-Files)|Grotesque]]\" by listening to the music from ''Jacob's Ladder''.<ref>Brian Lowry, ''The Truth is Out There: The Official Guide to the X-Files'', Harper Prism, 1995 (p.158).</ref> The music video for the 2010 song \"[[Nightmare (Avenged Sevenfold song)|Nightmare]]\" by [[Avenged Sevenfold]] is an [[Homage (arts)|homage]] to the famous hospital scene from the film, chosen by the director [[Wayne Isham]], because the band's deceased drummer [[The Rev]] was a fan of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2579240/avenged-sevenfold-nightmare-video-the-rev/|title=Avenged Sevenfold's Johnny Christ Talks Rev Tributes In 'Nightmare' Video|last=Archive-Kyle-Anderson|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Jacob's Ladder'' as a film is directly referred to in ''Silent Hill 2'' and especially ''Silent Hill 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/behind-mysteries-of-silent-hill |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130219221845/http://www.1up.com/features/behind-mysteries-of-silent-hill |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 19, 2013 |title=Behind the Many Mysteries of Silent Hill from |website=1UP.com |accessdate=June 28, 2013 }}</ref> Other references to the film itself include the mentions in the 2002 ''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' episode \"[[Night Route]]\" (dialog<ref>\"Remember Tim Robbins in ''Jacob's Ladder''? He dies in the beginning and spends the rest of the movie trying to accept his death.\"</ref>), the 2005 film ''[[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit]]'' (dialog), and the 2010 ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The Squirt and the Whale]]\" (visual).\n\nIn music, [[Claytown Troupe]] used a [[Sample (music)|sample]] of Michael's quote 'It's a fast trip ... ' at the beginning of the track \"Rainbow's Edge\" from their 1991 album ''Out There''. [[UNKLE]] sampled dialogue from the film in their 1998 \"[[Rabbit in Your Headlights]]\" and again in 2003 in \"Inside\". [[VNV Nation]]'s track \"Forsaken\" from the 1998 album ''[[Praise the Fallen]]'' ends with the quotation from Eckhart. \"Devils\" from [[IVardensphere]]'s 2011 album ''APOK'' begins with the same quotation. A sample of Jacob's cry 'Stop it, you're killing me!' is used in \"Next in Line\" from [[Nevermore]]'s 1996 album ''[[The Politics of Ecstasy (album)|The Politics of Ecstasy]]''. Terminal Sect extensively sampled the film for their track \"Where Angels Fall\".\n\nThe film's possible influence can be arguably seen in many other works ranging from [[M. Night Shyamalan]]'s 1999 hit psychological horror film ''[[The Sixth Sense]]''<ref>Charles Derry, ''Dark Dreams 2.0: A Psychological History of the Modern Horror Film from the 1950s to the 21st Century'', McFarland, 2009 (p.223).</ref> to [[Peter Arnett]]'s controversial 1998 [[CNN]] report \"Valley of Death\" about the 1970 [[Operation Tailwind]].<ref>Jerry Lembcke, ''CNN's Tailwind Tale: Inside Vietnam's Last Great Myth'', Rowman & Littlefield, 2003 (p.77).</ref> [[Jeff Millar]] of ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' wrote that [[Giuseppe Tornatore]]'s 1994 psychological thriller ''[[A Pure Formality]]'' uses the plot device of ''Jacob's Ladder'' mixed with several other sources.<ref>Jeff Millar, [http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/1995_1300653/pure-formality-so-pretentious-is-hurts.html 'Pure Formality' so pretentious is hurts], ''Houston Chronicle'', June 10, 1995.</ref> According to ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'', [[Massy Tadjedin]]'s 2005 psychological thriller ''[[The Jacket]]'' \"is a film for those who don't remember ''Jacob's Ladder'', perhaps for someone like Jacob himself,\" as it \"resembles ''Jacob's Ladder'' too much for its own good.\"<ref>Brian W. Fairbanks, ''I Saw That Movie, Too: Selected Film Reviews'', 2005 (p.201).</ref>\n\n==Remake==\n{{main|Jacob's Ladder (2019 film)}}\n\nThe remake was released in 2019, directed by [[David M. Rosenthal (director)|David M. Rosenthal]] and written by Jeff Buhler, Sarah Thorp, and Jake Wade Wall. The film stars [[Michael Ealy]], [[Jesse Williams (actor)|Jesse Williams]], [[Nicole Beharie]], [[Karla Souza]] and [[Guy Burnet]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Conspiracy fiction]] and [[paranoid fiction]]\n* [[Cotard delusion]]\n* [[List of anti-war films]]\n* [[List of films featuring hallucinogens]]\n* [[List of nonlinear narrative films]]\n* [[The Manchurian Candidate (1962 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]\n* [[Unethical human experimentation in the United States]]\n* [[Vietnam War in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0099871}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|jacobs_ladder}}\n* {{amg movie|25743}}\n* {{metacritic film|jacobs-ladder}}\n* [http://www.mrqe.com/movie_reviews/jacobs-ladder-m100045396 ''Jacob's Ladder''] at the [[Movie Review Query Engine]]\n\n{{Adrian Lyne}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacob's Ladder}}\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s war films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American war films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:Anti-war films]]\n[[Category:Carolco Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Death in art]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fiction with unreliable narrators]]\n[[Category:Films about angels]]\n[[Category:Films about nightmares]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Adrian Lyne]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Maurice Jarre]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1971]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1975]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot from the first-person perspective]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Horror war films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:Religious horror films]]\n[[Category:Religious war films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bruce Joel Rubin]]\n[[Category:Supernatural thriller films]]\n[[Category:Supernatural war films]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1990 film directed by Adrian Lyne}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Jacob's Ladder\n| image = Jacobsladderposter.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Adrian Lyne]]\n| producer = [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]\n| writer = [[Bruce Joel Rubin]]\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tim Robbins]]\n* [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]]\n* [[Danny Aiello]]\n}}\n| music = [[Maurice Jarre]]\n| cinematography = [[Jeffrey L. Kimball]]\n| editing = [[Tom Rolf]]\n| studio = [[Carolco Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[TriStar Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|1990|11|02}}\n| runtime = 113 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 113:02--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/jacobs-ladder-1970-3 | title=''Jacob's Ladder'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 6, 1990 | accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $25 million<ref name=nyt>Time Golden, [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/28/arts/film-up-jacob-s-ladder-and-into-the-hell-of-a-veteran-s-psyche.html Up 'Jacob's Ladder' And Into the Hell Of a Veteran's Psyche], ''The New York Times'', October 28, 1990.</ref>\n| gross = $26.1 million<ref name=mojo>{{mojo title|jacobsladder|Jacob's Ladder}}.</ref>\n}}\n'''''Jacob's Ladder''''' is a 1990 American [[psychological horror]] film directed by [[Adrian Lyne]], produced by [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]], written by [[Bruce Joel Rubin]], and starring [[Tim Robbins]], [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]], and [[Danny Aiello]]. The film's protagonist, Jacob, is a [[Vietnam veteran]] whose experiences prior to and during the war result in strange, fragmentary visions and bizarre hallucinations that continue to haunt him. As his ordeal worsens, Jacob desperately attempts to figure out the truth.\n\n''Jacob's Ladder'' was made by [[Carolco Pictures]] ten years after being written by Rubin. It drew from several inspirations for its story and effects, including the short film ''[[An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge (film)|An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge]]'', and the paintings of [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]]. Though only moderately successful upon release, the film garnered a [[Cult film|cult following]] and its plot and special effects became a source of influence for various other works such as the horror video game  ''[[Silent Hill]]''. A remake, also titled ''[[Jacob's Ladder (2019 film)|Jacob's Ladder]]'', was released in 2019.\n\n==Plot==\nOn October 6, 1971, an American [[infantryman]], Jacob Singer, is with the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Air Cavalry Division]], deployed in a village in Vietnam's [[Mekong Delta]], when his close-knit unit comes under sudden attack. As many of Jacob's comrades are killed or wounded, others exhibit abnormal behavior with some suffering [[catatonia]], convulsions, and seizures. Jacob flees into the jungle, only to be stabbed with a [[bayonet]] by an unseen assailant.\n\nJacob awakens in the [[New York City Subway]], where, after glimpsing what he believes to be a tentacle protruding from a sleeping homeless person, an inexplicably locked subway station exit results in him almost being hit by a train. The year is 1975, he works as a postal clerk, and lives in a rundown apartment in [[Brooklyn]] with his girlfriend, Jezebel. Jacob misses his old family and experiences visions of them, especially the youngest of his sons, Gabe, who had died in an accident before the war. Jacob is increasingly beset by disturbing experiences and apparitions, including glimpses of faceless vibrating figures, and narrowly escapes being run over by a pursuing car. He attempts to contact his regular doctor at the local [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|VA hospital]], but after first being told that there is no record of him ever being a patient there, Jacob is told that his doctor has died in a car explosion.\n\nAt a party thrown by friends, a [[psychic]] reads Jacob's palm and tells him that he is already dead, which Jacob dismisses as a joke. After declining to dance with her, he appears to witness an enormous tentacled creature having sex with and then impaling Jezzie through the mouth before he collapses. At home, Jacob experiences a dangerous fever, which Jezzie attempts to bring down with a painful ice bath. Jacob briefly wakes up in another reality where he lives with his wife and sons, including a still-alive Gabe. First-person perspective scenes of apparent [[Flashback (psychology)|flashbacks]] to his time in Vietnam show Jacob, badly wounded, being discovered by American soldiers before being evacuated under fire in a helicopter.\n\nOne of Jacob's former platoon mates, Paul, contacts him to reveal he is suffering from similar experiences, but is soon afterwards killed when his car explodes. Commiserating after the funeral, other surviving members of the platoon confess that they have all been experiencing horrifying hallucinations. Believing that they are suffering the effects of a military experiment performed on them without their knowledge or consent, they hire a lawyer to investigate. However the lawyer quits the case after reading military files documenting that the soldiers were never in combat and were discharged for psychological reasons. Jacob's comrades soon back down while Jacob suspects they have been threatened into doing so. He is abducted by suited men who try to intimidate him. Jacob fights them and escapes but is injured and nearly paralyzed in the process. He is taken to a nightmarish hospital, where he is told he has been killed and this is home, but his [[chiropractor]] friend Louis comes to his rescue and heals him. Louis quotes the 14th-century [[Christian mysticism|Christian mystic]], [[Meister Eckhart]]:\n\n<blockquote>Eckhart saw [[Hell]] too. He said: \"The only thing that burns in Hell is the part of you that won't let go of life, your memories, your attachments. They burn them all away. But they're not punishing you\", he said. \"They're freeing your soul. So, if you're frightened of dying and ... you're holding on, you'll see [[devil]]s tearing your life away. But if you've made your peace, then the devils are really [[angel]]s, freeing you from the earth.\"</blockquote>\n\nJacob is approached by a distressed man who was seen treating his wound in a [[Medical evacuation|medevac]] helicopter and who also dragged him away from Paul's burning car. Introducing himself as Michael Newman, he tells a story of having been a chemist with [[Chemical Corps|the Army's chemical warfare division]] where he designed a drug he called the Ladder, which massively increased aggression. Michael claims that, to test the drug's effectiveness, a dose was secretly given to Jacob's unit before the battle, causing some of them to turn on each other in a homicidal frenzy. Michael's story triggers a vision of Jacob's wounding in Vietnam, which shows his attacker as a fellow American soldier. Jacob returns to his family's home, where he finds Gabe, who takes him by the hand and leads him up the staircase into a bright light. The scene turns to a [[triage]] tent in 1971 as military doctors declare Jacob dead. The doctor notes that Jacob had put up a tremendous fight to stay alive, but looked peaceful in death.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as Jacob \"Professor\" Singer\n* [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]] as Jezebel \"Jezzie\" Pipkin\n* [[Danny Aiello]] as Louis \"Louie\" Denardo\n* [[Matt Craven]] as Michael Newman\n* [[Pruitt Taylor Vince]] as Paul Gruneger\n* [[Jason Alexander]] as Mr. Geary, the lawyer\n* [[Patricia Kalember]] as Sarah\n* [[Eriq La Salle]] as Frank\n* [[Ving Rhames]] as George\n* [[Brian Tarantina]] as Doug\n* Anthony Alessandro as Rod\n* [[Brent Hinkley]] as Jerry\n* [[S. Epatha Merkerson]] as Elsa\n* [[Kyle Gass]] as Tony\n* [[Lewis Black]] as Jacob's doctor\n* [[Perry Lang]] as Jacob's assailant\n* [[Macaulay Culkin]] (uncredited) as Gabe Singer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n{{quote box|quote=The horror of the movie would be in the revelation that hope is hell's final torment, that life is a dream that ends over and over with the final truth: that life was never real, that we are all creatures trapped in eternal suffering and damnation.|source=\u2013[[Bruce Joel Rubin]]<ref>Paul Meehan, ''Horror Noir: Where Cinema's Dark Sisters Meet'', McFarland, 2011 (p.259).</ref>|width=30%}}\n\nThe film's title refers to the Biblical story of [[Jacob's Ladder]], or the dream of a meeting place between [[Heaven]] and Earth ([[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 28:12). Its little-known alternative title is ''Dante's Inferno'', in a reference to ''[[Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]]'' by [[Dante Alighieri]].<ref>John Flowers, Paul Frizler, ''Psychotherapists on Film, 1899-1999: A Worldwide Guide to Over 5000 Films, Volume 1'', McFarland, 2004 (p.309).</ref><ref>Pamela Jaye Smith, ''Inner Drives'', Michael Wiese Productions, 2005 (p.217).</ref><ref>Eric G. Wilson, ''Secret Cinema: Gnostic Vision in Film'', Bloomsbury, 2006 (p.123).</ref> Screenwriter and co-producer [[Bruce Joel Rubin]] perceived the film as a modern interpretation of the ''[[Bardo Thodol|Liberation Through Hearing During the Intermediate State]]'', the [[Tibet]]an Book of the Dead.<ref name=\"st\">{{cite news | title = Adrian Lyne Met A Metaphysical Challenge | first = John | last = Hartl | url = http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19901101&slug=1101695 | work = [[The Seattle Times]] | date = November 1, 1990 | accessdate = February 6, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = FILM; Up 'Jacob's Ladder' And Into the Hell Of a Veteran's Psyche | first = Tim | last = Golden | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/28/arts/film-up-jacob-s-ladder-and-into-the-hell-of-a-veteran-s-psyche.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = October 28, 1990 | accessdate = October 22, 2007 }}</ref> Rubin said: \"The inspiration in a sense is my entire spiritual upbringing. Once you have a [[Buddhist meditation|meditative life]] you start to see that the world is really far different than what it appears to be. What appears to be finite is really couched in the infinite, and the infinite imbues everything in our lives.\"<ref>''Tricycle: The Buddhist Review - Volume 1'', Buddhist Ray, 1991 (p.77).</ref> Before writing his scripts for ''Jacob's Ladder'' and ''[[Ghost (1990 film)|Ghost]]'', which too was released in 1990, the Jewish-born Rubin spent two years in a [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan Buddhist]] monastery in Nepal;<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>Carrol Lee Fry, ''Cinema of the Occult: New Age, Satanism, Wicca, and Spiritualism in Film'', Associated University Presse, 2008 (p.77).</ref> previously, he has also written [[afterlife]]-themed ''[[Brainstorm (1983 film)|Brainstorm]]'' and ''[[Deadly Friend]]''.\n\nRubin's work on ''Jacob's Ladder'' began in 1980, sparked by his nightmare in which he dreamt about being trapped in a subway. For several years, Rubin tried to sell the script, without success; [[Thom Mount]] of [[Universal Pictures]] said he \"loved it, but it was not for his studio\". Directors [[Michael Apted]], [[Sidney Lumet]] and [[Ridley Scott]] all expressed an interest in making the film, but still no major studio was ready to invest in Rubin's \"too [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]]\" stories as \"Hollywood does not make [[List of ghost films|ghost movies]]\". Eventually, after ''Deadly Friend'' was filmed by [[Wes Craven]] in 1986, Rubin's screenplays for both ''Jacob's Ladder'' and ''Ghost'' were picked by [[Paramount Pictures]].<ref name=\"st\" /> In 1988,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> [[Adrian Lyne]], who described Rubin's work as \"certainly one of the best scripts I've ever read\", decided then to direct it instead of an adaptation of ''[[The Bonfire of the Vanities]]'' as he had originally planned (incidentally, [[Tom Hanks]], an actor originally considered by Lyne for the role of Jacob, ended up starring in ''Bonfire''). The ownership and policy changes at Paramount resulted in the cancellation of the project; the executives had doubts about the film's ending and the scenes taking place in Vietnam. The [[independent film]] studio [[Carolco Pictures]] decided to take over the production of ''Jacob's Ladder'', giving Lyne a greater creative control<ref name=\"st\" /> and a budget of $25 million.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Rubin became the film's co-producer, along with [[Mario Kassar]], [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]] and [[Andrew G. Vajna]].\n\n{{quote box|quote=I can see why people didn't want to make it for so long. It reads like a novel, and it's very intimidating because it's written so descriptively. Bruce had these very literal images of heaven and hell that I didn't know how to bring off. How do you introduce a character with horns?|source=\u2013[[Adrian Lyne]]<ref name=st/>|width=30%}}\n\nLyne, who downplayed Rubin's \"intimidating\" [[Old Testament]] themes,<ref name=\"after\">Tom Ruffles, ''Ghost Images: Cinema of the Afterlife'', McFarland, 2004 (p.192).</ref> said that he prepared for making the film by watching \"endless\" documentary films about the war in Vietnam and reading \"countless\" chronicles of [[near-death experience]]s.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> The film's plot device of a long period of [[Time perception|subjective time]] passing in an instant has been explored by several authors. A particularly strong inspiration for both Rubin and Lyne was [[Robert Enrico]]'s 1962 short film ''[[An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge (film)|An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge]]'',<ref name=\"rubin\">Bruce Joel Rubin, ''Jacob's Ladder'', Applause Theatre & Cinema Books, 1990.</ref> one of Lyne's favourite movies,<ref name=\"st\" /> which was in turn based on [[Ambrose Bierce]]'s 1890 short story [[An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge|of the same title]].\n\nCast in the role of Jacob, [[Tim Robbins]] said the film presented for him \"a great opportunity to go in a different direction. I love doing comedy, but I know I can do other things as well.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /> The film's military advisor was Vietnam veteran Captain [[Dale Dye]],<ref>Almar Haflidason, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/10/15/dale_dye_2001_2_interview.shtml Dale Dye: Part 2 - Stop Whining at Me!], BBC, October 2003.</ref> who provided a five-day [[Recruit training|boot camp]] military training for the actors playing soldiers in the Vietnam storyline (including Robbins, [[Pruitt Taylor Vince]], [[Eriq La Salle]] and [[Ving Rhames]]). The war scenes were filmed in the [[Puerto Rico]] area of [[Vega Baja]], featuring the [[UH-1 Iroquois|UH-1]] helicopters provided by the [[Puerto Rico National Guard]].\n\nAll of the film's special effect sequences were filmed in camera, with no use of post production effects. In several scenes of ''Jacob's Ladder'', Lyne used a [[body horror]] technique in which an actor is recorded shaking his head around at a low [[frame rate]], resulting in horrifically fast motion when played back. In the Special Edition's commentary track, Lyne said he was inspired by the art of the painter [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]] when developing the effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.widerscreenings.com/jacobsladder.html |title=Jacob's Ladder |publisher=Widerscreenings.com |date=|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> In his screenplay, Rubin used traditional imagery of demons and hell. However, Lyne decided to use images similar to [[thalidomide]] deformities to achieve a greater shock effect.<ref name=\"rubin\" /> After many heated arguments,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Lyne managed to convert Rubin to his vision. Lyne and Rubin used the works of the artist [[H. R. Giger]] and the photographers [[Diane Arbus]] and [[Joel-Peter Witkin]] for inspiration; another influence came from the [[Brothers Quay]]'s 1986 [[stop motion]] short film ''[[Street of Crocodiles]]''.\n\n{{quote box|quote=Vietnam was really a means to an end. It was a plot device rather than something we were trying to make a huge issue of.|source=\u2013[[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]<ref name=nyt/>|width=30%}}\n\nIn the film, Jacob is told by Michael that the horrific events he experienced on his final day in Vietnam were the product of an experimental drug called \"the Ladder\", which was used on troops without their knowledge. At the end of the film, a message is displayed saying that reports of testing of BZ, [[NATO]] code for a [[deliriant]] and [[hallucinogen]] known as [[3-Quinuclidinyl benzilate|3-quinuclidinyl benzilate]], on U.S. soldiers during the Vietnam War were denied by the [[United States Department of Defense|Pentagon]]. Lyne said a part of the inspiration for this motif was [[Martin A. Lee]]'s book ''[[Acid Dreams: The CIA, LSD and Sixties Rebellion]]'', but noted that \"nothing in the book suggests that the drug BZ \u2014 a super-hallucinogen that has a tendency to elicit [[Mania|maniac behavior]] \u2014 was used on U.S. troops.\"<ref name=\"st\" />\n\nAccording to Lyne's audio commentary, [[test screening]]s indicated that the initial version of the film was overwhelming for the audience. In response, about 20 minutes of disturbing scenes, mostly from the last third of the film, were removed from the final cut.\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical release===\n''Jacob's Ladder'' opened on November 2, 1990, distributed by [[TriStar Pictures]]. ''Jacob's Ladder: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' with the music by [[Maurice Jarre]] was released by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|author=Maurice Jarre |url=https://www.amazon.com/Jacobs-Ladder-Original-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B0000014RW |title=Jacob's Ladder: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref> Rubin's companion book, released by [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Applause Theater Book Publishers]] on the same day as the film,<ref name=\"st\" /> features a final draft of the screenplay, including the [[deleted scene]]s, and his essay on making of the screenplay and the film.<ref name=\"rubin\" />\n\n===Home media===\nThe Special Edition [[DVD]] was released by [[Artisan Entertainment]] on July 14, 1998, containing three deleted scenes (\"Jezzie's Transformation\", \"The Antidote\" and \"The Train Station\") along with several other special features, such as audio commentary by Adrian Lyne and a 26-minute [[making-of]] documentary \"Building ''Jacob's Ladder''\".<ref name=\"dvd\" /> On September 14, 2010, the film was released on [[Blu-ray Disc]] by [[Lions Gate Entertainment]] and retains all of the special features of the DVD version, along with two [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]]s, omitting only a TV spot that came with the DVD.<ref name=\"ign\">R.L. Shaffer, [http://uk.ign.com/articles/2010/09/14/jacobs-ladder-blu-ray-review Jacob's Ladder Blu-ray Review], IGN, September 14, 2010,</ref><ref name=\"br\" />\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film took the number one spot at the weekend [[box office]] in North America, garnering ticket sales of $7.5 million from 1,052 screens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-11-05/entertainment/ca-3119_1_ticket-sales |title='Jacob's Ladder' Climbs to Top of Ticket Sales. - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=August 17, 2000 |accessdate=June 28, 2013 |first=Pat H. |last=Broeske}}</ref> However, the attendance dropped fast and its overall domestic box office result was only $26,118,851.<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\n===Critical reception===\nAccording to aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 72% approval rating based on 64 reviews, with an average rating of 6.57/10. The site's consensus reads: \"Even with its disorienting leaps of logic and structure, ''Jacob's Ladder'' is an engrossing, nerve-shattering experience\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jacobs_ladder/|title=Jacob's Ladder (1990)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C-\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' wrote that watching it left him \"reeling with turmoil and confusion, with feelings of sadness and despair,\" and called it a \"thoroughly painful and depressing experience \u2014 but, it must be said, one that has been powerfully written, directed and acted.\" He awarded the film three and a half out of a possible four stars.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19901102/REVIEWS/11020301/1023 | title = Jacob's Ladder | last = Ebert | first = Roger | date = November 2, 1990 | publisher = Rogerebert.suntimes.com | accessdate = April 16, 2010 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that this \"slick, riveting, viscerally scary film about what in other hands would be a decidedly unsalable subject, namely [[death]],\" is \"both quaint and devastating.\"<ref>Janet Maslin, [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE7D8143CF931A35752C1A966958260 Movie Review - Jacob s Ladder - Review/Film; It's Scary, Yes, and Death Has a Role], ''The New York Times'', November 2, 1990.</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Desson Thomson]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' felt disappointed with the film that is \"ultimately flat on its [[Surrealism|surrealistic]] face, the victim of too many fake-art sequences.\"<ref>Desson Howe, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/jacobsladderrhowe_a0b2b5.htm 'Jacob's Ladder' (R)], ''Washington Post'', November 2, 1990.</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that \"''Jacob's Ladder'' is so 'dark' it sucks Robbins right down with it. By the time Jacob is being strapped to a bed and wheeled down a hospital corridor strewn with bloody limbs, it's hard to care whether the [[Orwellian]] image is a hallucination or not. You just want out.\"<ref>Owen Gleiberman, [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318521,00.html Jacob's Ladder (1990)], EW.com, November 2, 1990.</ref> [[Kim Newman]] called the film \"effectively the blunt remake\" of ''[[Carnival of Souls]]''.<ref name=\"after\" />\n\nAccording to [[IGN]]'s review of the DVD release in 2004, \"After movies like ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Se7en]]'', it may not pack the same subtle horror for today's audiences it did when it was first released, but it's still a great film.\"<ref name=\"dvd\">Mike Drucker, [http://uk.ign.com/articles/2004/11/08/jacobs-ladder Jacob's Ladder: The living nightmare of a movie has a pretty decent DVD.], IGN, November 8, 2004.</ref> IGN's review of ''Jacob's Ladder''{{'}}s 2010 Blu-ray release called it \"an emotionally poignant, creepy horror masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"ign\" /> According to ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', ''Jacob's Ladder'' is \"a bizarrely cohesive hybrid of war movie, character study, [[art film]], and horror flick\" and \"the very act of watching the film is so emotionally draining that the viewer leaves the film feeling worked-in; the thought of repeat viewings is daunting yet insatiable.\"<ref name=\"br\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/jacobs-ladder/1807 |title=Jacob's Ladder <nowiki>&#124;</nowiki> DVD Review |magazine=Slant Magazine |date=September 14, 2010 |accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref> [[John Kenneth Muir]] called the film's nightmarish hospital scene \"one of the most terrifying moments in all of 1990s horror cinema.\" Muir further wrote: \"In its musings about death, about the end we all fear'', Jacob's Ladder'' proves a deeply affecting and meaningful motion picture. After a screening, you'll immediately want to hug the people you love and then go outside and breathe the fresh air, or otherwise affirm your very existence.\"<ref>John Kenneth Muir, ''Horror Films of the 1990s'', McFarland, 2011 (p.105).</ref>\n\nRubin's script was included on the list of \"Hollywood's ten best unproduced screenplays\" by ''American Film'' magazine in 1983.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In 1991, ''Jacob's Ladder'' was nominated at [[Horror Hall of Fame]] II for best horror film, losing to ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]''. The film was also featured in [[Bravo (U.S. TV channel)|Bravo]]'s 2004 documentary miniseries ''[[The 100 Scariest Movie Moments]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030070540/http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml |archivedate=October 30, 2007 |title=The 100 Scariest Movie Moments: 100 Scariest Moments in Movie History - Official Bravo TV Site |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref> and in the 2009 book ''[[1001 Movies You Must See Before You Die]]''. In 2013, the [[Jacob Burns Film Center]] projectionist Andrew Robinson chose it as his favourite scary movie.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.burnsfilmcenter.org/halloween-countdown-day-8-jacobs-ladder/ |title=Halloween Countdown \u2013 Day 8: Jacob's Ladder \u00bb Jacob Burns Film Center Blog |publisher=Blog.burnsfilmcenter.org |date=October 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 23, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728200336/http://blog.burnsfilmcenter.org/halloween-countdown-day-8-jacobs-ladder/ |archivedate=July 28, 2014  }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''Jacob's Ladder'' greatly inspired the horror  ''[[Silent Hill]]'',<ref>John Gaudiosi, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/johngaudiosi/2012/11/02/resident-evil-and-silent-hill-producer-samuel-hadida-talks-wolfenstein-and-onimusha-movies/ Resident Evil And Silent Hill Producer Samuel Hadida Talks Wolfenstein And Onimusha Movies],  Forbes, February 11, 2012.</ref> including the video games ''[[Silent Hill (video game)|Silent Hill]]'' (1999),<ref>Bernard Perron, ''Silent Hill: The Terror Engine'', University of Michigan Press, 2012 (p. 55-56).</ref> ''[[Silent Hill 2]]'' (2001),<ref>[http://uk.ign.com/articles/2001/08/17/interview-with-silent-hill-2s-artist-takayoshi-sato Interview with Silent Hill 2&#039,s Artist Takayoshi Sato], IGN, August 17, 2001.</ref> ''[[Silent Hill 3]]'' (2003),<ref>[http://uk.ign.com/articles/2002/06/12/silent-hill-3-interview Silent Hill 3 Interview], IGN, June 12, 2002</ref> ''[[Silent Hill 4: The Room]]'' (2004),<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/collective/A3066879| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227080553/http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/collective/A3066879| archivedate = December 27, 2007| title = Silent Hill 4: The Room| author = Daniel Etherington| work = [[bbc.co.uk]]| date = October 1, 2004| accessdate = June 9, 2007}}</ref> and ''[[Silent Hill: Homecoming]]'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|last=Grayson |first=Vincent |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/52765/silent-hill-5-interview-jasons |title=Silent Hill 5 Interview: Jason's Philosophy, Jacob's Ladder, and Pyramid Head |publisher=Shacknews.com |date=|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> as well as the series' 2006 [[Silent Hill (film)|film adaptation]] by [[Christophe Gans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/219 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328090017/http://bloody-disgusting.com/interview/219 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 28, 2016 |title=Interview Silent Hill: Director Christophe Gans |publisher=Bloody Disgusting |accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> The film's influence on their works was also recognised by [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]], writer of the 2011 TV series ''[[American Horror Story: Asylum]]'',<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/03/jessica-lange-the-name-game_n_2402373.html Jessica Lange Sings 'The Name Game': 'American Horror Story: Asylum' Goes Musical], HUFFPOST TV, March 1, 2013</ref> and by [[Shinji Mikami]], director of the 2014 video game ''[[The Evil Within]]''.<ref name=ign2>Lucy O'Brien, [http://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/05/06/the-movie-every-survival-horror-fan-should-watch \"Am I dying, Louie?\"], IGN, May 16, 2013.</ref> [[Kim Manners]] prepared for directing ''[[The X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Grotesque (The X-Files)|Grotesque]]\" by listening to the music from ''Jacob's Ladder''.<ref>Brian Lowry, ''The Truth is Out There: The Official Guide to the X-Files'', Harper Prism, 1995 (p.158).</ref> The music video for the 2010 song \"[[Nightmare (Avenged Sevenfold song)|Nightmare]]\" by [[Avenged Sevenfold]] is an [[Homage (arts)|homage]] to the famous hospital scene from the film, chosen by the director [[Wayne Isham]], because the band's deceased drummer [[The Rev]] was a fan of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2579240/avenged-sevenfold-nightmare-video-the-rev/|title=Avenged Sevenfold's Johnny Christ Talks Rev Tributes In 'Nightmare' Video|last=Archive-Kyle-Anderson|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Jacob's Ladder'' as a film is directly referred to in ''Silent Hill 2'' and especially ''Silent Hill 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/behind-mysteries-of-silent-hill |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130219221845/http://www.1up.com/features/behind-mysteries-of-silent-hill |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 19, 2013 |title=Behind the Many Mysteries of Silent Hill from |website=1UP.com |accessdate=June 28, 2013 }}</ref> Other references to the film itself include the mentions in the 2002 ''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' episode \"[[Night Route]]\" (dialog<ref>\"Remember Tim Robbins in ''Jacob's Ladder''? He dies in the beginning and spends the rest of the movie trying to accept his death.\"</ref>), the 2005 film ''[[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit]]'' (dialog), and the 2010 ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The Squirt and the Whale]]\" (visual).\n\nIn music, [[Claytown Troupe]] used a [[Sample (music)|sample]] of Michael's quote 'It's a fast trip ... ' at the beginning of the track \"Rainbow's Edge\" from their 1991 album ''Out There''. [[UNKLE]] sampled dialogue from the film in their 1998 \"[[Rabbit in Your Headlights]]\" and again in 2003 in \"Inside\". [[VNV Nation]]'s track \"Forsaken\" from the 1998 album ''[[Praise the Fallen]]'' ends with the quotation from Eckhart. \"Devils\" from [[IVardensphere]]'s 2011 album ''APOK'' begins with the same quotation. A sample of Jacob's cry 'Stop it, you're killing me!' is used in \"Next in Line\" from [[Nevermore]]'s 1996 album ''[[The Politics of Ecstasy (album)|The Politics of Ecstasy]]''. Terminal Sect extensively sampled the film for their track \"Where Angels Fall\".\n\nThe film's possible influence can be arguably seen in many other works ranging from [[M. Night Shyamalan]]'s 1999 hit psychological horror film ''[[The Sixth Sense]]''<ref>Charles Derry, ''Dark Dreams 2.0: A Psychological History of the Modern Horror Film from the 1950s to the 21st Century'', McFarland, 2009 (p.223).</ref> to [[Peter Arnett]]'s controversial 1998 [[CNN]] report \"Valley of Death\" about the 1970 [[Operation Tailwind]].<ref>Jerry Lembcke, ''CNN's Tailwind Tale: Inside Vietnam's Last Great Myth'', Rowman & Littlefield, 2003 (p.77).</ref> [[Jeff Millar]] of ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' wrote that [[Giuseppe Tornatore]]'s 1994 psychological thriller ''[[A Pure Formality]]'' uses the plot device of ''Jacob's Ladder'' mixed with several other sources.<ref>Jeff Millar, [http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/1995_1300653/pure-formality-so-pretentious-is-hurts.html 'Pure Formality' so pretentious is hurts], ''Houston Chronicle'', June 10, 1995.</ref> According to ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'', [[Massy Tadjedin]]'s 2005 psychological thriller ''[[The Jacket]]'' \"is a film for those who don't remember ''Jacob's Ladder'', perhaps for someone like Jacob himself,\" as it \"resembles ''Jacob's Ladder'' too much for its own good.\"<ref>Brian W. Fairbanks, ''I Saw That Movie, Too: Selected Film Reviews'', 2005 (p.201).</ref>\n\n==Remake==\n{{main|Jacob's Ladder (2019 film)}}\n\nThe remake was released in 2019, directed by [[David M. Rosenthal (director)|David M. Rosenthal]] and written by Jeff Buhler, Sarah Thorp, and Jake Wade Wall. The film stars [[Michael Ealy]], [[Jesse Williams (actor)|Jesse Williams]], [[Nicole Beharie]], [[Karla Souza]] and [[Guy Burnet]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Conspiracy fiction]] and [[paranoid fiction]]\n* [[Cotard delusion]]\n* [[List of anti-war films]]\n* [[List of films featuring hallucinogens]]\n* [[List of nonlinear narrative films]]\n* [[The Manchurian Candidate (1962 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]\n* [[Unethical human experimentation in the United States]]\n* [[Vietnam War in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0099871}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|jacobs_ladder}}\n* {{amg movie|25743}}\n* {{metacritic film|jacobs-ladder}}\n* [http://www.mrqe.com/movie_reviews/jacobs-ladder-m100045396 ''Jacob's Ladder''] at the [[Movie Review Query Engine]]\n\n{{Adrian Lyne}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacob's Ladder}}\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s war films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American war films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:Anti-war films]]\n[[Category:Carolco Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Death in art]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fiction with unreliable narrators]]\n[[Category:Films about angels]]\n[[Category:Films about nightmares]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Adrian Lyne]]