{"title_page": "Franz Seldte", "text_new": "{{Short description|Leader of Stahlhelm from 1920 to 1935}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2008}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Franz Seldte\n| image         = FranzSeldte1933.jpeg \n| caption       = Photograph by Robert Sennecke, 1933\n| office        = [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Reich Minister for Labour]]\n| term_start    = 30 January 1933\n| term_end      = 23 May 1945\n| president     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Paul von Hindenburg]]<br/>(1933\u20131934)|[[Adolf Hitler]] (1934\u20131945;<br/>as ''[[Fuhrer]]'')|[[Karl D\u00f6nitz]] (1945)}}\n| chancellor    = {{Unbulleted list|[[Adolf Hitler]] (1934\u20131945)|[[Joseph Goebbels]] (1945)|[[Lutz Graf Schwerin von Krosigk]] (1945; as Leading Minister)}}\n| predecessor   = [[Friedrich Syrup]]\n| title2        = Federal Leader of the ''Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund'' (''Stahlhelm'')\n| term_start2   = 28 March 1934\n| term_end2     = 7 November 1935\n| title3        = Federal Leader of ''[[Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|Der Stahlhelm]]''\n| term_start3   = 25 December 1918\n| term_end3     = 28 March 1934\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1882|06|29}}\n| birth_place   = [[Magdeburg]], [[German Empire|Germany]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1947|04|01|1882|06|29}}\n| death_place   = [[F\u00fcrth]], [[Allied-occupied Germany|Germany]]\n| resting_place = St Laurentius Cemetery, [[Rottach-Egern]], [[Germany]]\n| party         = [[National Socialist German Workers' Party]] (1933\u20131945)\n| otherparty    = [[German National People's Party]] (until 1933)\n| alma_mater    = [[Brunswick University of Technology]]\n| signature     = Franz Seldte signature.svg\n| allegiance    = {{flag|German Empire}}\n| branch        = {{Nowrap|{{flagicon|German Empire|naval}} [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]]}}\n| rank          = ''[[Hauptmann|Hauptmann d.R.]]'' \n| unit          = 66th Infantry Regiment\n| battles       = [[World War I]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme]]{{WIA}}\n| mawards       = {{Unbulleted list|[[Iron Cross First Class]]|Iron Cross Second Class|[[Wound Badge]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Franz Seldte''' (29 June 1882{{spaced ndash}}1 April 1947) was a German politician who served as the [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Reich Minister for Labour]] from 1933 to 1945.<ref>Stackelberg (2007). ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany'', p. 243.</ref> Prior to his ministry, Seldte served as the Federal Leader of ''[[Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|Der Stahlhelm]]'' [[World War I]] ex-[[Serviceman|servicemen]]'s organisation from 1918 to 1934. Ideologically, he identified as a [[national conservative]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Magdeburg]] in the [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] province of [[Province of Saxony|Saxony]], Seldte was the son of an owner of a factory producing chemical products and soda water.<ref>Stackelberg (2007). ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany'', p. 243.</ref> He attended the Wilhelm-Raabe-[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] in Magdeburg and, after an apprenticeship as a salesman, studied chemistry at the universities of [[Braunschweig University of Technology|Braunschweig]] and [[University of Greifswald|Greifswald]]. In 1908 he took over the business of his early deceased father.<ref>Wistrich (2001). ''Who's Who In Nazi Germany'', p. 232.</ref> As an officer of the [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]] he was wounded in [[World War I]] and lost his left arm.<ref>Stackelberg (2007). ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany'', p. 243.</ref>  He then became a front reporter. Awarded with the [[Iron Cross]] 2nd and 1st class,<ref>Snyder (1976). ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', p. 320.</ref> Seldte also was promoted to the rank of ''[[Hauptmann|Hauptmann d.R.]]'' in the 66th Infantry Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n==''Der Stahlhelm''==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-01258, Hugenberg, von Stephani und Seldte.jpg|thumb|left|270px|Seldte (r.) with Hugenberg and the Berlin Stahlhelm leader von Stephani at a rally against the Young-Plan, [[Berlin Sportpalast]], 1929]]\nAs a reaction to the [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919]], Seldte founded ''Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten'' on 25 December 1918, agitating against the [[Treaty of Versailles]] and German [[World War I reparations|war reparations]]. According to Seldte, the organization was to use the spirit of the ''Frontsoldaten'' against the \u2018swinish revolution\u2019 taking place in Germany under the Weimar government.<ref>Snyder (1976). ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', p. 320.</ref> While he took charge of ''Der Stahlhelm'' from 1923 onwards, he had to cope with the constant rivalry of his deputy leader, the militant [[Theodor Duesterberg]].\n\nSeldte became a member of the national conservative [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP) and was a member of the Magdeburg city council (''Stadtrat'').{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\nDuring the later years of the [[Weimar Republic]] ''Der Stahlhelm'' became increasingly anti-democratic and anti-republican. However, Seldte hoped that the organization could become a leading organ of a united right-wing movement. In 1929 it united its forces with the DNVP under [[Alfred Hugenberg]], the [[Pan-German League]] and the [[Nazi Party]] to initiate a [[1929 German referendum|German referendum]] against the [[Young Plan]] on [[World War I reparations]].<ref>Kershaw (2000). ''Hitler: 1889-1936, Hubris'', p. 310, 356.</ref>  The common goal was to denounce the Chancellor [[Hermann M\u00fcller (politician)|Hermann M\u00fcller]] and his ministers as traitors to their country, nevertheless the plebiscite failed to reach the [[quorum]]. In 1931 Seldte helped create the short-lived [[Harzburg Front]],<ref>Zentner & Bed\u00fcrftig, eds. ''The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', vol. 2, (M-Z), p. 869.</ref> a right-wing alliance against the government of M\u00fcller's successor [[Heinrich Br\u00fcning]].\n\n==Minister for Labour==\nDuring the negotiations for the Chancellorship of Germany between [[Franz von Papen]] and Hitler in mid-January 1933, Seldte threw his vote and ''Der Stahlhelm'' behind Hitler, after which, Papen acquiesced to Hitler\u2019s demands.<ref>Longerich (2012). ''Heinrich Himmler'', p. 144.</ref> On the day of the ''[[Machtergreifung]]'' on 30 January 1933, Seldte joined the [[Hitler Cabinet]] as Reich Minister for Labour,<ref>Shirer (1990). ''The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich'', p. 184.</ref> once again outdoing his long-time rival Duesterberg. In the run-up to the [[March 1933 German federal election|elections of March 1933]] ''Der Stahlhelm'' together with Hugenberg's national conservative [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP) attempted to make the ''Kampffront Schwarz-Wei\u00df-Rot'' (\"[[National colours of Germany|Black White Red]] Combat Front\") into the dominant political camp on the right, but ultimately failed as it only gained 8.0% of the votes cast.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} Nevertheless, Seldte obtained a seat in the ''[[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]]'' parliament as a DNVP \"guest\".{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nOn 27 April 1933 Seldte finally joined the Nazi Party and merged ''Der Stahlhelm'' into [[Ernst R\u00f6hm]]'s ''[[Sturmabteilung]] (SA)'' militia \u2013 de facto placing it at the disposal of Hitler.<ref>Bracher (1970). ''The German Dictatorship: The Origins, Structure, and Effects of National Socialism'', p. 222.</ref> In August 1933, he was awarded the rank of ''SA-[[Obergruppenf\u00fchrer]]'' and later was appointed [[Reichskommissar]] for the ''Freiwilliger Arbeitsdienst'' employment program, but was soon superseded by his state secretary [[Konstantin Hierl]] as leader of the ''[[Reichsarbeitsdienst]]'' organization.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} In March 1934 Seldte was made the federal leader of the ''Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund (Stahlhelm)'' ({{lang-en|National Socialist German Combatants' Federation (Stahlhelm)}}) (NSDFBSt), a successor organization of ''Der Stahlhelm'', which however was soon disbanded.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} In 1935 he requested to be released from official responsibilities, but Hitler refused.\n\nThroughout his tenure as chief of the Labor Ministry, Seldte never enjoyed the full support of Hitler, who did not think he was worth much. As a result, members of the Nazi hierarchy began encroaching on his areas of responsibility and Seldte was marginalized accordingly.<ref>Fischer (1995). ''Nazi Germany: A New History'', p. 315.</ref> For instance, Hermann Goering\u2019s Four Year Plan which he began to implement in late 1936, ran roughshod over Seldte's Labor Ministry altogether.<ref>Evans (2006). ''The Third Reich in Power'', p. 358.</ref> Seldte, without substantial power, remained Reich Minister for Labour until the end of [[World War II]] and was also a member of the [[Free State of Prussia (1933\u20131947)|Prussian]] government under Minister president [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]] as State Labour Minister. Even after Hitler\u2019s suicide and the nomination of Grand-Admiral D\u00f6nitz as his successor, Seldte kept his post, being accordingly named Labour Minister.<ref>Mazower (2009). ''Hitler\u2019s Empire: How the Nazis Ruled Europe'', pp. 532\u2013533.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nSeldte was captured and arrested in [[Mondorf-les-Bains]] at the end of the war.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} During the Nuremberg trials, Seldte tried to exonerate himself by claiming that he had stood against the dictatorship of Hitler and that he advocated for a two-chamber system of parliamentary governance.<ref>Taylor & Shaw (2002). ''Dictionary of the Third Reich'', p. 261.</ref> His story was not convincing. Seldte died in a US military hospital in April 1947 at [[F\u00fcrth]], before the Nuremberg Tribunal had the chance to formally arraign him on charges.<ref>Snyder (1976). ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', p. 320.</ref>\n\nDuring the time of [[Nazi Germany]], streets were named after him in several German cities, among them his hometown Magdeburg and [[Leverkusen]].<ref>[http://www.leverkusen.com/strasse/index.php4?view=Seldte Franz-Seldte-Str. (ehemalig)]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Bracher, Karl D. ''The German Dictatorship: The Origins, Structure, and Effects of National Socialism''. New York: Praeger Publishers, 1970.\n* Evans, Richard J. ''The Third Reich in Power''. New York: Penguin, 2006.\n* Fischer, Klaus. ''Nazi Germany: A New History''. New York: Continuum, 1995.\n* Kershaw, Ian. ''Hitler: 1889-1936, Hubris''. New York: W. W. Norton & Company, 2000.\n* Longerich, Peter. ''Heinrich Himmler''. Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press, 2012.\n* Mazower, Mark. ''Hitler\u2019s Empire: How the Nazis Ruled Europe''. New York: Penguin, 2009.\n* Shirer, William L. ''The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich''. New York: MJF Books, 1990, [1959].\n* Snyder, Louis L. ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich''. London: Robert Hale, 1976\n* Stackelberg, Roderick. ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany''. New York: Routledge, 2007.\n* Taylor, James, and Warren Shaw. ''Dictionary of the Third Reich''. New York: Penguin, 2002.\n* Wistrich, Robert S. ''Who's Who In Nazi Germany''. New York: Routledge, 2001.\n* Zentner, Christian, and Friedemann Bed\u00fcrftig, eds. ''The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', vol. 2 (M-Z). New York: Macmillan Publishing, 1991.\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/016337}}\n\n{{Hitler's Cabinet}}\n{{Cabinet Schwerin von Krosigk}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Conservatism|Germany|Politics|World War I|World War II}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seldte, Franz}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:German National People's Party politicians]]\n[[Category:German Nazi politicians]]\n[[Category:German people of World War II]]\n[[Category:German Protestants]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Nazi Germany ministers]]\n[[Category:Nazis who served in World War I]]\n[[Category:People from Magdeburg]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Stahlhelm members]]\n[[Category:University of Greifswald alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Leader of Stahlhelm from 1920 to 1935}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2008}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Franz Seldte\n| image         = FranzSeldte1933.jpeg \n| caption       = Franz Seldte in 1933\n| office        = [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Reich Minister for Labour]]\n| term_start    = 30 January 1933\n| term_end      = 23 May 1945\n| president     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Paul von Hindenburg]]<br/>(1933\u20131934)|[[Adolf Hitler]] (1934\u20131945;<br/>as ''[[Fuhrer]]'')|[[Karl D\u00f6nitz]] (1945)}}\n| chancellor    = {{Unbulleted list|[[Adolf Hitler]] (1934\u20131945)|[[Joseph Goebbels]] (1945)|[[Lutz Graf Schwerin von Krosigk]] (1945; as Leading Minister)}}\n| predecessor   = [[Friedrich Syrup]]\n| title2        = Federal Leader of the ''Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund'' (''Stahlhelm'')\n| term_start2   = 28 March 1934\n| term_end2     = 7 November 1935\n| title3        = Federal Leader of ''[[Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|Der Stahlhelm]]''\n| term_start3   = 25 December 1918\n| term_end3     = 28 March 1934\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1882|06|29}}\n| birth_place   = [[Magdeburg]], [[German Empire|Germany]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1947|04|01|1882|06|29}}\n| death_place   = [[F\u00fcrth]], [[Allied-occupied Germany|Germany]]\n| resting_place = St Laurentius Cemetery, [[Rottach-Egern]], [[Germany]]\n| party         = [[National Socialist German Workers' Party]] (1933\u20131945)\n| otherparty    = [[German National People's Party]] (until 1933)\n| alma_mater    = [[Brunswick University of Technology]]\n| signature     = Franz Seldte signature.svg\n| allegiance    = {{flag|German Empire}}\n| branch        = {{Nowrap|{{flagicon|German Empire|naval}} [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]]}}\n| rank          = ''[[Hauptmann|Hauptmann d.R.]]'' \n| unit          = 66th Infantry Regiment\n| battles       = [[World War I]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme]]{{WIA}}\n| mawards       = {{Unbulleted list|[[Iron Cross First Class]]|Iron Cross Second Class|[[Wound Badge]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Franz Seldte''' (29 June 1882{{spaced ndash}}1 April 1947) was a German politician who served as the [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Reich Minister for Labour]] from 1933 to 1945.<ref>Stackelberg (2007). ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany'', p. 243.</ref> Prior to his ministry, Seldte served as the Federal Leader of ''[[Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|Der Stahlhelm]]'' [[World War I]] ex-[[Serviceman|servicemen]]'s organisation from 1918 to 1934. Ideologically, he identified as a [[national conservative]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Magdeburg]] in the [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] province of [[Province of Saxony|Saxony]], Seldte was the son of an owner of a factory producing chemical products and soda water.<ref>Stackelberg (2007). ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany'', p. 243.</ref> He attended the Wilhelm-Raabe-[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] in Magdeburg and, after an apprenticeship as a salesman, studied chemistry at the universities of [[Braunschweig University of Technology|Braunschweig]] and [[University of Greifswald|Greifswald]]. In 1908 he took over the business of his early deceased father.<ref>Wistrich (2001). ''Who's Who In Nazi Germany'', p. 232.</ref> As an officer of the [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]] he was wounded in [[World War I]] and lost his left arm.<ref>Stackelberg (2007). ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany'', p. 243.</ref>  He then became a front reporter. Awarded with the [[Iron Cross]] 2nd and 1st class,<ref>Snyder (1976). ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', p. 320.</ref> Seldte also was promoted to the rank of ''[[Hauptmann|Hauptmann d.R.]]'' in the 66th Infantry Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n==''Der Stahlhelm''==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-01258, Hugenberg, von Stephani und Seldte.jpg|thumb|left|270px|Seldte (r.) with Hugenberg and the Berlin Stahlhelm leader von Stephani at a rally against the Young-Plan, [[Berlin Sportpalast]], 1929]]\nAs a reaction to the [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919]], Seldte founded ''Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten'' on 25 December 1918, agitating against the [[Treaty of Versailles]] and German [[World War I reparations|war reparations]]. According to Seldte, the organization was to use the spirit of the ''Frontsoldaten'' against the \u2018swinish revolution\u2019 taking place in Germany under the Weimar government.<ref>Snyder (1976). ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', p. 320.</ref> While he took charge of ''Der Stahlhelm'' from 1923 onwards, he had to cope with the constant rivalry of his deputy leader, the militant [[Theodor Duesterberg]].\n\nSeldte became a member of the national conservative [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP) and was a member of the Magdeburg city council (''Stadtrat'').{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\nDuring the later years of the [[Weimar Republic]] ''Der Stahlhelm'' became increasingly anti-democratic and anti-republican. However, Seldte hoped that the organization could become a leading organ of a united right-wing movement. In 1929 it united its forces with the DNVP under [[Alfred Hugenberg]], the [[Pan-German League]] and the [[Nazi Party]] to initiate a [[1929 German referendum|German referendum]] against the [[Young Plan]] on [[World War I reparations]].<ref>Kershaw (2000). ''Hitler: 1889-1936, Hubris'', p. 310, 356.</ref>  The common goal was to denounce the Chancellor [[Hermann M\u00fcller (politician)|Hermann M\u00fcller]] and his ministers as traitors to their country, nevertheless the plebiscite failed to reach the [[quorum]]. In 1931 Seldte helped create the short-lived [[Harzburg Front]],<ref>Zentner & Bed\u00fcrftig, eds. ''The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', vol. 2, (M-Z), p. 869.</ref> a right-wing alliance against the government of M\u00fcller's successor [[Heinrich Br\u00fcning]].\n\n==Minister for Labour==\nDuring the negotiations for the Chancellorship of Germany between [[Franz von Papen]] and Hitler in mid-January 1933, Seldte threw his vote and ''Der Stahlhelm'' behind Hitler, after which, Papen acquiesced to Hitler\u2019s demands.<ref>Longerich (2012). ''Heinrich Himmler'', p. 144.</ref> On the day of the ''[[Machtergreifung]]'' on 30 January 1933, Seldte joined the [[Hitler Cabinet]] as Reich Minister for Labour,<ref>Shirer (1990). ''The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich'', p. 184.</ref> once again outdoing his long-time rival Duesterberg. In the run-up to the [[March 1933 German federal election|elections of March 1933]] ''Der Stahlhelm'' together with Hugenberg's national conservative [[German National People's Party]] (DNVP) attempted to make the ''Kampffront Schwarz-Wei\u00df-Rot'' (\"[[National colours of Germany|Black White Red]] Combat Front\") into the dominant political camp on the right, but ultimately failed as it only gained 8.0% of the votes cast.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} Nevertheless, Seldte obtained a seat in the ''[[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]]'' parliament as a DNVP \"guest\".{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nOn 27 April 1933 Seldte finally joined the Nazi Party and merged ''Der Stahlhelm'' into [[Ernst R\u00f6hm]]'s ''[[Sturmabteilung]] (SA)'' militia \u2013 de facto placing it at the disposal of Hitler.<ref>Bracher (1970). ''The German Dictatorship: The Origins, Structure, and Effects of National Socialism'', p. 222.</ref> In August 1933, he was awarded the rank of ''SA-[[Obergruppenf\u00fchrer]]'' and later was appointed [[Reichskommissar]] for the ''Freiwilliger Arbeitsdienst'' employment program, but was soon superseded by his state secretary [[Konstantin Hierl]] as leader of the ''[[Reichsarbeitsdienst]]'' organization.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} In March 1934 Seldte was made the federal leader of the ''Nationalsozialistischer Deutscher frontk\u00e4mpfer-Bund (Stahlhelm)'' ({{lang-en|National Socialist German Combatants' Federation (Stahlhelm)}}) (NSDFBSt), a successor organization of ''Der Stahlhelm'', which however was soon disbanded.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} In 1935 he requested to be released from official responsibilities, but Hitler refused.\n\nThroughout his tenure as chief of the Labor Ministry, Seldte never enjoyed the full support of Hitler, who did not think he was worth much. As a result, members of the Nazi hierarchy began encroaching on his areas of responsibility and Seldte was marginalized accordingly.<ref>Fischer (1995). ''Nazi Germany: A New History'', p. 315.</ref> For instance, Hermann Goering\u2019s Four Year Plan which he began to implement in late 1936, ran roughshod over Seldte's Labor Ministry altogether.<ref>Evans (2006). ''The Third Reich in Power'', p. 358.</ref> Seldte, without substantial power, remained Reich Minister for Labour until the end of [[World War II]] and was also a member of the [[Free State of Prussia (1933\u20131947)|Prussian]] government under Minister president [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]] as State Labour Minister. Even after Hitler\u2019s suicide and the nomination of Grand-Admiral D\u00f6nitz as his successor, Seldte kept his post, being accordingly named Labour Minister.<ref>Mazower (2009). ''Hitler\u2019s Empire: How the Nazis Ruled Europe'', pp. 532\u2013533.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nSeldte was captured and arrested in [[Mondorf-les-Bains]] at the end of the war.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} During the Nuremberg trials, Seldte tried to exonerate himself by claiming that he had stood against the dictatorship of Hitler and that he advocated for a two-chamber system of parliamentary governance.<ref>Taylor & Shaw (2002). ''Dictionary of the Third Reich'', p. 261.</ref> His story was not convincing. Seldte died in a US military hospital in April 1947 at [[F\u00fcrth]], before the Nuremberg Tribunal had the chance to formally arraign him on charges.<ref>Snyder (1976). ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', p. 320.</ref>\n\nDuring the time of [[Nazi Germany]], streets were named after him in several German cities, among them his hometown Magdeburg and [[Leverkusen]].<ref>[http://www.leverkusen.com/strasse/index.php4?view=Seldte Franz-Seldte-Str. (ehemalig)]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Bracher, Karl D. ''The German Dictatorship: The Origins, Structure, and Effects of National Socialism''. New York: Praeger Publishers, 1970.\n* Evans, Richard J. ''The Third Reich in Power''. New York: Penguin, 2006.\n* Fischer, Klaus. ''Nazi Germany: A New History''. New York: Continuum, 1995.\n* Kershaw, Ian. ''Hitler: 1889-1936, Hubris''. New York: W. W. Norton & Company, 2000.\n* Longerich, Peter. ''Heinrich Himmler''. Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press, 2012.\n* Mazower, Mark. ''Hitler\u2019s Empire: How the Nazis Ruled Europe''. New York: Penguin, 2009.\n* Shirer, William L. ''The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich''. New York: MJF Books, 1990, [1959].\n* Snyder, Louis L. ''Encyclopedia of the Third Reich''. London: Robert Hale, 1976\n* Stackelberg, Roderick. ''The Routledge Companion to Nazi Germany''. New York: Routledge, 2007.\n* Taylor, James, and Warren Shaw. ''Dictionary of the Third Reich''. New York: Penguin, 2002.\n* Wistrich, Robert S. ''Who's Who In Nazi Germany''. New York: Routledge, 2001.\n* Zentner, Christian, and Friedemann Bed\u00fcrftig, eds. ''The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich'', vol. 2 (M-Z). New York: Macmillan Publishing, 1991.\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/016337}}\n\n{{Hitler's Cabinet}}\n{{Cabinet Schwerin von Krosigk}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Conservatism|Germany|Politics|World War I|World War II}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seldte, Franz}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:German National People's Party politicians]]\n[[Category:German Nazi politicians]]\n[[Category:German people of World War II]]\n[[Category:German Protestants]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Nazi Germany ministers]]\n[[Category:Nazis who served in World War I]]\n[[Category:People from Magdeburg]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Stahlhelm members]]\n[[Category:University of Greifswald alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Lieutcoluseng", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copyedit (minor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Seldte"}
{"title_page": "Edwin Halstead", "text_new": "{{short description|English athlete}}\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = \n| name             = Edwin \"Eddie\" Halstead\n| image            = \n| image_size       = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.-->\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Edith Halstead\n| fullname         = \n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = {{ENG}}\n| citizenship      = \n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = 1907<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=BqBMIRXSfIh38DaGSiLEnQ&scan=1|title=Births Dec 1907|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Citation doesn't confirm that this is the same Halstead that is discussed in this article.|date=April 2020}}\n| birth_place      = [[Radcliffe, Greater Manchester|Radcliffe]]\n| death_date       = 1962 (aged 54)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=ZCTmYJGgzuwGegxYYQuL3g&scan=1|title=Deaths Jun 1962|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Citation doesn't confirm that this is the same Halstead that is discussed in this article.|date=April 2020}}\n| death_place      = [[Blackpool]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| years_active     = \n| website          = \n| country          = \n| sport            = \n| event            = \n| league           = \n| league_type      = \n| employer         = \n| agent            = \n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| universityteam   = \n| club             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| partner          = \n| former_partner   = \n| coach            = \n| coaching         = \n| retired          = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n| pb               = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Athletics}}\t\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\t\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games|British Empire Games]]}}\t\n{{MedalSilver| [[1934 British Empire Games|1934 London]]|[[Athletics at the 1934 British Empire Games|Javelin]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Edwin \"Eddie\" Halstead''' (1907-1962), formerly '''Edith Halstead''', was an [[England|English]] [[Athletics (sport)|athlete]]. Halstead won a [[silver medal]] in the women's [[javelin throw]] at the [[1934 British Empire Games]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/41327|title=Athletes and Results|publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref> \n\n[[Nellie Halstead|Halstead's sister Nellie]] also competed in the 1934 Games and won three medals.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/nellie-halstead-1.html|title=Nellie Halstead Biogrpahy|publisher=Sports Reference}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Sports-reference.com may not be reliable.|date=April 2020}} \n\nLater, as part of a [[gender transition]], Halstead changed his name to Edwin.<ref name=\"SR\" />{{Better source|reason=Sports-reference.com may not be reliable.|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halstead, Edith}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:English javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for England]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1934 British Empire Games]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual men]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual sportspeople]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT track and field athletes]]\n\n{{England-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English athlete}}\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = \n| name             = Edwin \"Eddie\" Halstead\n| image            = \n| image_size       = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.-->\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Edith Halstead\n| fullname         = \n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = {{ENG}}\n| citizenship      = \n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = 1907<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=BqBMIRXSfIh38DaGSiLEnQ&scan=1|title=Births Dec 1907|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Citation doesn't confirm that this is the same Halstead that is discussed in this article.|date=April 2020}}\n| birth_place      = [[Radcliffe, Greater Manchester|Radcliffe]]\n| death_date       = 1962 (aged 54)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=ZCTmYJGgzuwGegxYYQuL3g&scan=1|title=Deaths Jun 1962|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Citation doesn't confirm that this is the same Halstead that is discussed in this article.|date=April 2020}}\n| death_place      = [[Blackpool]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| years_active     = \n| website          = \n| country          = \n| sport            = \n| event            = \n| league           = \n| league_type      = \n| employer         = \n| agent            = \n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| universityteam   = \n| club             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| partner          = \n| former_partner   = \n| coach            = \n| coaching         = \n| retired          = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n| pb               = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Athletics}}\t\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\t\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games|British Empire Games]]}}\t\n{{MedalSilver| [[1934 British Empire Games|1934 London]]|[[Athletics at the 1934 British Empire Games|Javelin]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Edwin \"Eddie\" Halstead''' (1907-1962), formerly '''Edith Halstead''', was an [[England|English]] [[Athletics (sport)|athlete]]. Halstead won a [[silver medal]] in the women's [[javelin throw]] at the [[1934 British Empire Games]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/41327|title=Athletes and Results|publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref> Halstead's sister, [[Nellie Halstead]], also competed in the 1934 Games and won three medals.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/nellie-halstead-1.html|title=Nellie Halstead Biogrpahy|publisher=Sports Reference}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=Sports-reference.com may not be reliable.|date=April 2020}} Later, as part of a [[gender transition]], Halstead changed his name to Edwin.<ref name=\"SR\" />{{Better source|reason=Sports-reference.com may not be reliable.|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halstead, Edith}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:English javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for England]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1934 British Empire Games]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual men]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual sportspeople]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT track and field athletes]]\n\n{{England-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WanderingWanda", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tweaks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edwin_Halstead"}
{"title_page": "Rose Namajunas", "text_new": "{{short description|American mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Luke Harris\n| other_names     = Thug Rose \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = Rose Gertrude Namajunas\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1992|6|29}}\n| birth_place     = [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| residence       = \n| nationality     = American\n| ethnicity       = Lithuanian\n| height          = 5 ft 5 in<ref name=UFC192stats>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufc.com/event/UFC192/printFightCard|title=Fight Card - UFC 192 Cormier vs. Gustafsson|publisher=UFC.com|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref>\n| weight          = 115 lb\n| weight_class    = [[Strawweight (MMA)|Strawweight]]\n| reach           = 65 in\n| reach_footnote  = <ref name=UFC192stats />\n| fighting_out_of = Denver, Colorado, U.S.\n| team            = 303 Training Center<ref>{{cite AV media |last1=Bryant |first1=Karyn |author-link1=Karyn Bryant |date=10 April 2017 |title=Rose Namajunas Predicts 1st Round KO Of Michelle Waterson At UFC On FOX |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OsfaxyHYTuE&t=8m58s |access-date=3 May 2017 |time=08:58}}</ref><br />[[Grudge Training Center]] (2012\u20132016)<br />[[Minnesota Martial Arts Academy]] (2011\u20132012)\n| trainer         = [[Trevor Wittman]]<br />Tony Basile\n| rank            = Black belt in [[Taekwondo]]<ref name=UFCprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Rose-Namajunas|title=Rose Namajunas - Official UFC Fighter Profile|publisher=UFC.com|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref><br />Black belt in [[Karate]]<ref name=\"Rose Namajunas Awakening Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awakeningfighters.com/athletes/rose-namajunas|title=Rose Namajunas Awakening Profile|publisher=Awakeningfighters.com|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref><ref name=UFCprofile/><br />Brown belt in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]]<ref>{{cite AV media |last=Namajunas |first=Rose |date=August 28, 2016 |title=Thug Diaries: Episode 1 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=owhxCi4WMsY&t=9m6s |access-date=2 January 2017 |time=9:06}}</ref>\n| years_active    = 2010\u2013present ([[MMA]])\n| mma_kowin       = 1\n| mma_subwin      = 5\n| mma_decwin      = 2\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = 1\n| mma_decloss     = 2\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = \n| sherdog         = 69083\n| footnotes       = \n| updated         = \n}}\n\n'''Rose Gertrude Namajunas''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|n|\u0251\u02d0|m|\u0259|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|n|\u0259|s}}; born June 29, 1992) is an American [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]].<ref name=\"TUF20NSAC\">{{cite web|url=http://boxing.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/boxingnvgov/content/results/2014_Results/TUF_SEASON_20.pdf|title=Mixed martial arts results: Season 20 \u2013 The Ultimate Fighter|website=Nevada State Athletic Commission|access-date=}}</ref> She is currently signed to the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC), where she competes in the [[Strawweight (MMA)|women's strawweight division]]. Namajunas is a former [[List of UFC Champions#Women's Strawweight Championship|UFC Women's Strawweight Champion]]. As of  February 10, 2020, she is #2 in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship rankings#Women's strawweight|UFC women's strawweight rankings]] and #6 in [[List of current UFC fighters#Rankings|UFC women's pound-for-pound rankings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/rankings|title=Rankings {{!}} UFC|website=www.ufc.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNamajunas was born in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] on {{birth date|1992|6|29}}, to Lithuanian parents. She was named Rose ({{lang-lt|Ro\u017e\u0117}}) in honor of her great-grandmother Ro\u017e\u0117 Got\u0161alkait\u0117 Namaj\u016bnien\u0117, whose husband was an [[Act of Independence of Lithuania|independent]] [[Lithuania]] military officer. He was killed by the [[Soviet]]s near his house in the [[Temporary capital of Lithuania|temporary capital]] [[Kaunas]], Lithuania. Rose Namajunas regularly visits Lithuania and understands the [[Lithuanian language]], because she communicates in it with her grandparents.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rimkus |first1=K\u0119stas |title=Kov\u0173 super\u017evaig\u017ed\u0117 Ro\u017e\u0117 Namajunas vaik\u0161to po Kaun\u0105: \u201eGeriausia vieta \u2013 mo\u010diut\u0117s sodas\u201c |url=https://www.15min.lt/sportas/naujiena/kovinis-sportas/kovu-superzvaigzde-roze-namajunas-vaiksto-po-kauna-geriausia-vieta-mociutes-sodas-864-1187406 |website=[[15min.lt]] |accessdate=12 August 2019 |language=lt}}</ref>\n\nShe has said that her father suffered from [[schizophrenia]], which led to complications and hardships during her youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2740757-joanna-jedrzejczyk-uses-rose-namajunas-mental-health-struggles-for-trash-talk|title=Joanna Jedrzejczyk Uses Rose Namajunas' Mental Health Struggles For Trash Talk|publisher=BleacherReport.com|date=2017-10-25|accessdate=2017-11-05}}</ref>\nNamajunas started practicing Taekwondo at the age of 5. She earned her poom belt (junior black belt) at age 9. After that, she went on to practice both karate and jiu-jitsu. While in high school, she started training in kickboxing and mixed martial arts with [[Duke Roufus]] at Roufusport, and she was also a senior-year wrestler at [[Milwaukee High School of the Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/news/435804/Rose-Namajunas-To-survive-is-to-find-meaning-in-the-suffering/|title=Rose Namajunas: To survive is to find meaning in the suffering|publisher=MixedMartialArts.com|date=2013-02-10|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fightland.vice.com/blog/rose-namajunas|title=Rose Namajunas talks TUF, Colorado, and Trying to Start a Fight with Royce Gracie|last=Jennings|first=L.A.|date=June 3, 2014|website=[[Fightland]]|access-date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n\n===Early career===\nNamajunas began competing in MMA as an amateur in 2010. She trained under Greg Nelson at [[Minnesota Martial Arts Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/news/Rose-Namajunas-To-survive-is-to-find-meaning-in-the-suffering|title=\nRose Namajunas: To survive is to find meaning in the suffering |publisher=mixedmartialarts.com|date=2013-02-10|accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref> She racked up a perfect amateur record of 4-0 with 2 wins by TKO and 2 by decision. Both of the finishes came in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2012/12/27/3804512/rose-namajunas-hopes-to-build-on-what-ronda-rousey-has-done-for-wmma|title=Rose Namajunas hopes to build on what Ronda Rousey has done for WMMA|publisher=BloodyElbow.com|date=2012-12-27|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref>\n\n===Invicta Fighting Championship===\nShe made her professional debut against [[Emily Kagan]] at [[Invicta FC events#Invicta FC 4: Esparza vs. Hyatt|Invicta FC 4: Esparza vs. Hyatt]] on January 5, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2012/11/invicta-fc-4-official-with-esparza-gadelha-title-fight-baszler-davis-and-more|title=Invicta FC 4 official with Esparza-Gadelha title fight, Baszler-Davis and more|publisher=MMAjunkie.com|date=2012-11-23|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref> After two back-and-forth rounds, Namajunas was able to secure the victory via submission due to a rear-naked choke in round three. The victory in her pro debut also earned her the ''Submission of the Night'' bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2013/01/05/four-fighters-earn-bonuses-at-invicta-fighting-championships-4/|title=Four Fighters Earn Bonuses At Invicta Fighting Championships 4|publisher=MMARising.com|date=2013-01-05|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref>\n\nIn her second professional appearance, Namajunas faced Kathina Catron at [[Invicta FC events#Invicta FC 5: Penne vs. Waterson|Invicta FC 5: Penne vs. Waterson]] on April 5, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmarising.com/news/2013/02/11/rose-namajunas-vs-kathina-catron-set-for-invicta-fc-5-card/|title=Rose Namajunas vs Kathina Catron Set For Invicta FC 5 Card|publisher=MMARising.com|date=2013-02-11|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/02/invicta-fc-5-official-for-april-5-in-kansas-city-mo|title=Invicta FC 5 official for April 5 in Kansas City, Mo.|publisher=MMAjunkie.com|date=2013-02-11|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref> She won the fight by submission due to a flying armbar just 12 seconds into the first round. This performance garnered Namajunas her second Invicta ''Submission of the Night'' award.<ref name=Ifive>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2013/04/06/invicta-fc-5-bonuses-kaufman-vs-smith-wins-fight-of-the-night/|title=Invicta FC 5 Bonuses: Kaufman vs Smith Wins Fight Of The Night, KO of the Night goes to Nakamoto and Sub of the Night to Namajunas|publisher=MMARising.com|date=2013-04-06|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas fought fellow undefeated prospect [[Tecia Torres]] at [[Invicta FC events#Invicta FC 6: Coenen vs. Cyborg|Invicta FC 6: Coenen vs. Cyborg]] on July 13, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmarising.com/news/2013/04/19/rose-namajunas-vs-tecia-torres-added-to-invicta-fc-6-card/|title=Rose Namajunas vs Tecia Torres Added To Invicta FC 6 Card|publisher=MMARising.com|date=2013-04-19|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/04/invicta-fc-6-set-for-july-13-13-bout-lineup-set-with-santos-coenen-headliiner|title=Invicta FC 6 set for July 13, 13-bout lineup set with Santos-Coenen headliner|publisher=MMAjunkie.com|date=2013-04-20|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref> Namajunas lost the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prommanow.com/2013/07/13/invicta-fc-6-live-results-and-play-by-play/|title=Invicta FC 6 live results and play-by-play|publisher=ProMMANow.com|date=2013-07-13|accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2013/7/13/4520430/wmma-invicta-fc-6-cyborg-santos-justino-vs-marloes-coenen-live-streaming-video-results-play-by-play|title=Invicta FC 6: Cris \"Cyborg\" Justino vs Marloes Coenen Live Streaming Video, Results, and Play by Play|publisher=BloodyElbow.com|date=2013-07-13|accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref>\n\n===''The Ultimate Fighter''===\nOn December 11, 2013, it was announced that Namajunas was signed by the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) along with 10 other strawweight fighters to compete on season 20 of ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]'', which would crown the first-ever UFC strawweight champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2013/12/ufc-acquires-11-fighters-from-invicta-fc-launches-womens-strawweight-division-with-tuf-20/|title=UFC acquires 11 fighters from Invicta FC, launches women's strawweight division with 'TUF 20'|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2013-12-11}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas was the fourth pick by coach [[Gilbert Melendez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/09/episode-no-1-recap-the-ultimate-fighter-20-team-pettis-vs-team-melendez|title=Episode No. 1 recap: 'The Ultimate Fighter 20: Team Pettis vs Team Melendez'|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2014-09-11}}</ref> She defeated [[Alex Chambers]] by submission due to a rear-naked choke in the preliminary round of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2014/11/5/7160451/tuf-20-results-recap-alex-chambers-vs-rose-namajunas-ep-7-fox-sports-1-mma|title=TUF 20 results and recap for Alex Chambers vs Rose Namajunas (Ep. 7)|publisher=mmamania.com|date=2014-11-05}}</ref>\n\nIn the quarter-finals, Namajunas faced [[Joanne Calderwood]]. She won the fight via kimura in the second round.\n\nIn the semi-finals, Namajunas faced [[Randa Markos]]. She again won the fight via kimura in the first round.\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nNamajunas faced [[Carla Esparza]] at [[The Ultimate Fighter: A Champion Will Be Crowned#The Ultimate Fighter 20 Finale|The Ultimate Fighter: A Champion Will Be Crowned Finale]] on December 12, 2014, for the vacant UFC Strawweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/12/carla-esparza-vs-rose-namajunas-set-for-strawweight-title-headliner-at-tuf-20-finale|title=Carla Esparza vs. Rose Namajunas set for strawweight title headliner at TUF 20 Finale|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2014-12-10}}</ref> Namajunas lost the fight as she was submitted via rear-naked choke in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/12/tuf-20-finale-results-carla-esparza-taps-rose-namajunas-to-win-strawweight-title|title=TUF 20 Finale results: Carla Esparza taps Rose Namajunas to win strawweight title|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2014-12-13}}</ref>\n\nDespite losing in the finale, Namajunas was awarded two season $25,000 bonus awards for ''Performance of the Season'' and ''Fight of the Season'' for her bout with [[Joanne Calderwood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/12/namajunas-wins-50000-markos-and-calderwood-25000-tuf-20-season-bonu|title=Namajunas wins $50,000, Markos and Calderwood $25,000 'TUF 20' season bonuses|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2014-12-13|accessdate=2014-12-13}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas was expected to face [[Nina Ansaroff]] on May 23, 2015, in a preliminary bout at [[UFC 187]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/02/ansaroff-namajunas-sampo-scoggins-kuntz-makhachev-added-to-mays-ufc-187-lineup|title=Ansaroff-Namajunas, Sampo-Scoggins, Kuntz-Makachev added to Mays UFC 187 lineup|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2015-02-25}}</ref> Prior to the fight, Ansaroff missed weight by 4 pounds and was fined 20 percent of her fight purse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/05/ufc-187-live-and-official-weigh-in-results|title=UFC 187 weigh-in results|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2015-05-22}}</ref> The bout was scrapped entirely a couple hours before the event, as Ansaroff was declared medically unfit to compete due to illness. According to Ansaroff's camp, she contracted the flu the week before, and the weight cut exacerbated the illness, forcing Ansaroff to abandon her weight cut early, and ultimately withdraw from the fight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/illness-forces-ansaroff-off-ufc-187-team-hopeful-for-rescheduled-date-with-namajunas-052315?nav=false|title=Illness forces Ansaroff off UFC 187, team hopeful for rescheduled date with Namajunas|last=Cepeda|first=Elias|date=May 23, 2015|work=FOX Sports|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> Though the fight couldn't take place, Namajunas was paid her full fight purse (show- and win money).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/06/late-fight-cancellations-heres-what-happens-with-ufcs-new-athlete-outfitting-policy|title=Late fight cencellations? Here's what happens with UFC's new athlete outfitting policy|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2015-06-13}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas fought [[Angela Hill (fighter)|Angela Hill]] on October 3, 2015, at [[UFC 192]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/08/ufc-192-adds-joseph-benavidez-vs-ali-bagautinov-rose-namajunas-vs-angela-hill|title=UFC 192 adds Joseph Benavidez vs Ali Bagautinov, Rose Namajunas vs Angela Hill|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2015-08-17}}</ref> After some back-and-forth striking exchanges on the feet, Namajunas took Hill down with a trip off a punch. As Hill stood up, Namajunas quickly secured a rear-naked choke, submitting Hill in the first round.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2015/10/3/9447417/ufc-192-results-rose-namajunas-chokes-out-angela-hill-in-the-first|title=UFC 192 results: Rose Namajunas chokes out Angela Hill in the first round|last=Thomas|first=Luke|date=October 3, 2015|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a quick turnaround, Namajunas faced streaking prospect [[Paige VanZant]] in the main event of [[UFC Fight Night 80]] on December 10, 2015, replacing an injured [[Joanne Calderwood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2015/10/28/9625066/paige-vanzant-vs-rose-namajunas-joanne-calderwood-out-ufc|title=Paige VanZant now fighting Rose Namajunas with Calderwood out|publisher=bloodyelbow.com|author=Anton Tabuena|date=2015-10-28|accessdate=2015-10-28}}</ref> Namajunas dominated VanZant throughout the fight, out-striking her consistently and landing eight takedowns. She attempted three submissions\u2014two armbars and a rear naked choke\u2014before she won the fight midway through the fifth round via submission due to a rear naked choke.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2015/12/11/9890604/ufc-fight-night-80-results-rose-namajunas-dominates-a-resilient-paige|title=UFC Fight Night 80 results: Rose Namajunas dominates a resilient Paige VanZant|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Dave Doyle|date=2015-12-11|accessdate=2015-12-11}}</ref> The win also earned Namajunas her first ''Performance of the Night'' bonus award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/12/ufc-fight-night-80-bonuses-namajunas-earns-50000-for-domination-of-vanzant|title=UFC Fight Night 80 bonuses: Namajunas earns $50,000 for domination of VanZant|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2015-12-11|accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2016, Namajunas faced the still-undefeated [[Tecia Torres]] at [[UFC on Fox 19]] in a rematch of their 2013 fight at Invicta FC 6. Namajunas won the fight via close but unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2016/4/16/11445516/ufc-on-fox-19-results-rose-namajunas-edges-tecia-torres-in-well|title=UFC on FOX 19 results: Rose Namajunas edges Tecia Torres in well-contested scrap|last=Doyle|first=Dave|date=April 16, 2019|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 2016, Namajunas fought [[Karolina Kowalkiewicz]] at [[UFC 201]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/06/rose-namajunas-meets-undefeated-karolina-kowalkiewicz-at-ufc-201-in-atlanta|title=Rose Namajunas meets undefeated Karolina Kowalkiewicz at UFC 201 in Atlanta|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=MMAjunkie Staff|date=2016-05-06|accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> in a match regarded as a title eliminator. Kowalkiewicz defeated Namajunas via split decision.<ref>{{cite news|URL=http://www.mmamania.com/2016/7/31/12334918/ufc-201-results-karolina-kowalkiewicz-splits-rose-namajunas-joanna-jedrzejczyk|title=UFC 201 results: Karolina Kowalkiewicz splits Rose Namajunas, likely sets up all-Polish title fight with Joanna Jedrzejczyk|publisher=mmamania.com|author=Thomas Myers|date=2016-07-31|accessdate=2016-08-04}}</ref> Both participants were awarded ''Fight of the Night'' for their performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/7/31/12335150/ufc-201-bonuses-rose-namajunas-and-karolina-kowalkiewicz-take-home|title=UFC 201 bonuses: Rose Namajunas and Karolina Kowalkiewicz take home FOTN honors|publisher=mmafighting.com|date=2016-07-31}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas faced [[Michelle Waterson]] on April 15, 2017, at [[UFC on Fox 24]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/02/ufc-heads-to-kansas-city-for-first-time-for-ufc-on-fox-24-including-namajunas-waterson|title=UFC heads to Kansas City for first time for UFC on FOX 24|website=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|accessdate=2017-02-11|date=2017-02-11}}</ref> Namajunas dropped Waterson with a head kick, and won by submission due to a rear-naked choke in round 2, marking the 5th submission finish in her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/04/ufc-on-fox-24-results-rose-namajunas-submission-win-michelle-waterson|title=UFC on FOX 24 results: Rose Namajunas dominates Michelle Waterson, earns submission win|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2017-04-15}}</ref>\n\n====Strawweight Champion====\nNamajunas faced Strawweight champion [[Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk]] at [[UFC 217]] at Madison Square Garden in New York on November 4, 2017. She came in as a big underdog against the undefeated champion. However, Namajunas upset the MMA world when she knocked J\u0119drzejczyk down, once behind the ear and then again with a left hand to her chin. She won the fight by KO in first round to be crowned the new [[List of UFC Champions#Women's Strawweight Championship|UFC Women's Strawweight Champion]].<ref name=\"MMAjunkie\">{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/11/ufc-217-results-rose-namajunas-stuns-heavy-favorite-joanna-jedrzejczyk-to-win-strawweight-title|title=UFC 217 results: Rose Namajunas KOs Joanna Jedrzejczyk to win title in huge upset|date=2017-11-05|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2017-11-05|language=en-US}}</ref> This win also earned Namajunas her second [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]] bonus award.<ref name=\"mmajunkie.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/11/ufc-217-bonuses-title-fight-winners-namajunas-dillashaw-st-pierre-get-extra-50000|title=UFC 217 bonuses: Title winners Namajunas, Dillashaw, St-Pierre get extra $50,000|date=2017-11-05|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2017-11-05|language=en-US}}</ref> This was Namajunas' first knockout victory in her professional career (2 TKO-wins as an amateur). Her victory was immediately declared one of the biggest upsets in UFC history. At the UFC 217 post-fight press conference, Namajunas stated that she intended to use her champion status as a platform to spread awareness of mental illness.<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/11/5/16607350/ufc-217-post-fight-press-conference-video</ref>\n\nIn the first defense of her title, Namajunas faced J\u0119drzejczyk in a rematch that took place on April 7, 2018, at [[UFC 223]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Namajunas-Joanna 2 Heads to Brooklyn|url=http://www.ufc.com/news/Namajunas-Joanna-2-heads-to-Brooklyn|publisher=UFC|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> She won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2018/04/joanna-jedrzejczyk-shocked-at-ufc-223-loss-tells-strawweights-bow-down-rose-namajunas|title=Joanna Jedrzejczyk shocked at UFC 223 loss to Namajunas, tells other strawweights: 'Bow down'|date=2018-04-08|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-04-08|language=en-US}}</ref> Namajunas spent the remainder of the year recovering from a lingering case of [[spinal stenosis]] from a [[cervical vertebrae|C6 vertebral]] [[vertebral compression fracture|compression fracture]], symptoms of which manifested while training with [[Valentina Shevchenko (fighter)|Valentina]] and [[Antonina Shevchenko]] in 2017, and had intensified during training camp for UFC 223.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Episode 1: A New Chapter |url=http://play.podtrac.com/espn-arielhelwanismmashow/c.espnradio.com/s:5L8r1/audio/3519607/fiverounds_2018-06-25-184207.64k.mp3 |access-date=2019-01-08 |series=Ariel Helwani's MMA Show |first=Ariel |last=Helwani |network=ESPN |date=2018-06-25 |number=1 |time=2:00:30}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |title=Episode 11: De La Hoya, Northcutt, Perry, Usman, Faber, Iaquinta, many more |url=http://play.podtrac.com/espn-arielhelwanismmashow/c.espnradio.com/s:5L8r1/audio/3542978/fiverounds_2018-09-04-170918.64k.mp3 |access-date=2019-01-08 |series=Ariel Helwani's MMA Show |first=Ariel |last=Helwani |network=ESPN |date=2019-09-04 |number=11 |time=1:40:40}}</ref>\n\nIn her second title defense, Namajunas faced [[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]] in the main event at [[UFC 237]] on May 11, 2019, in Andrade's home country of Brazil, in what would be Namajunas' first MMA fight outside the United States. Despite dominating the Brazilian throughout the first round and the beginning of the second, she lost the fight by KO via a slam in the second round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/25709796/rose-namajunas-defend-strawweight-belt-vs-jessica-andrade-ufc-237|title=Rose Namajunas to defend strawweight belt vs. Jessica Andrade at UFC 237|last=Okamoto|first=Brett|date=2019-01-07|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/05/12/ufc-237-results-namajunas-vs-andrade/|title=UFC 237 Results: Jessica Andrade Weathers Storm, Slams Rose Namajunas To Win Strawweight Title|last=Anderson|first=Jay|date=2019-05-12|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> This fight earned her the [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|''Fight of the Night'']] award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/05/ufc-237-bonuses-new-champ-jessica-andrade-takes-home-100k|title=UFC 237 bonuses: New champ Jessica Andrade takes home $100K|date=2019-05-12|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas is scheduled to face [[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]] for a rematch on April 18, 2020 at [[UFC 249]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/rose-namajunas-vs-jessica-andrade-officially-confirmed-for-ufc-249|title=Rose Namajunas vs Jessica Andrade officially confirmed for UFC 249|date=2020-01-11|website=www.sportskeeda.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==Fighting style==\nNamajunas utilizes forward movement while pressuring opponents with jabs and high kicks.<ref name=Isix>{{cite news |last=Sargent |first=Robert |title=Invicta Fighting Championships 6 Live Play-By-Play & Results lookout |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2013/07/13/invicta-fighting-championships-6-live-play-by-play-results/ |accessdate=August 11, 2014 |newspaper=mmarising.com |date=July 13, 2013}}</ref> During her fight at Invicta FC 6, she directed a series of axe kicks, front kicks, and forward roundhouse kicks to her opponent's head.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hemminger |first=Brian |title=Invicta FC 6 results |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2013/7/13/4519832/invicta-fc-6-results-and-live-fight-coverage-for-coenen-vs-cyborg-2 |accessdate=August 11, 2014 |newspaper=mmamania.com |date=July 13, 2013}}</ref> After closing the distance, she will sometimes attempt to grapple and execute a submission.<ref name=Ifive/><ref name=Isix/>\n\n==Personal life==\nNamajunas is the fianc\u00e9e and training partner of former [[Glory World Series|Glory]] and UFC heavyweight [[Pat Barry (fighter)|Pat Barry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmatko.com/pat-barry-and-girlfriend-rose-namajunas-at-the-2012-world-mma-awards/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116080135/http://www.mmatko.com/pat-barry-and-girlfriend-rose-namajunas-at-the-2012-world-mma-awards/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-01-16|title=Pat Barry And Girlfriend Rose Namajunas At The 2012 World MMA Awards|publisher=MMATKO.com|date=2013-01-14|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref><ref name=\"CP201304\">{{cite  web|url=http://www.cagepotato.com/interview-rose-namajunas-discusses-thug-life-pat-barrys-charm-and-her-invicta-fc-5-fight-this-friday/|title=Interview: Rose Namajunas Discusses Thug Life, Pat Barry\u2019s Charm, And Her Invicta FC 5 Fight This Friday|last=Goldstein|first=Ben|date=April 3, 2013|website=CagePotato|access-date=June 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1597302-ufc-pat-barry-goes-nuts-over-girlfriend-rose-namajumas-invicta-fc-armbar-win|title=UFC's Pat Barry Goes Nuts Over Girlfriend Rose Namajunas' Invicta FC Armbar Win|publisher=BleacherReport.com|date=2013-04-08|accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref>\n\nNamajunas's moniker, \"Thug Rose\", was given by friends when she was young because of her intimidating scowl.<ref name=\"CP201304\" />\n\n{{Cquote|\nI got it [nickname] from my neighborhood friends. When I was little, I was the only white girl, I was smaller than everyone else, and for some reason I just acted harder than everybody else \u2014 just fearless, you know? So they kind of dubbed me that because of the intimidating scowl I always had on my face. That's what gave me that name.<ref name=\"CP201304\" />\n}}\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*[[2018 ESPY Awards#Winners and nominees|2018 ESPY Award]] for [[Best Fighter ESPY Award|Best Fighter]] (nominee)<ref>{{cite press release |date=June 20, 2018 |title=The 2018 ESPYS Nominees |url=https://espnmediazone.com/us/the-2018-espys-nominees/ |type=Press release |publisher= |agency=ESPN MediaZone |access-date=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[2018 Kids' Choice Sports Awards#Biggest Powerhouse|Kids' Choice Sports 2018 Award for Biggest Powerhouse]] (nominee)<ref>{{cite press release |date=June 12, 2018 |title=Motor sports pioneer Danica Patrick to be honored with the Legend Award at Nickelodeon's Kids' Choice Sports 2018 |url=http://www.nickpress.com/press-releases/2018/06/12/motor-sports-pioneer-danica-patrick-to-be-honored-with-the-legend-award-at-nickelodeons-kids-choice-sports-2018 |type=Press release |location=[[Burbank, California]] |publisher=Nickelodeon |agency=}}</ref>\n*Eighth Annual Real Women Awards - 2017 Woman of the Year<ref name=\"RWA2017\">{{cite web|url=http://promotingrealwomen.com/eighth-annual-real-women-award-winners/|title=Eighth Annual Real Women Award Winners|last=Adams|first=Jason|date=January 18, 2018|website=Promoting Real Women|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128190516/promotingrealwomen.com/eighth-annual-real-women-award-winners/|archive-date=January 28, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[List of UFC Champions#Women's Strawweight Championship|UFC Women's Strawweight Championship]] (One time)\n**One successful title defense <small> vs. [[Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk]] </small><ref name=\"MMAjunkie\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n**[[Bonus Awards|Performance of the Night]] (Two times) <small>vs. [[Paige VanZant]] and [[Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-Fight-Night-Bonuses-Namajunas-Chiesa-Miller-Means-Garner-3650K-96993|title=UFC Fight Night bonuses: Namajunas, Chiesa, Miller, Means garner $50K|publisher=sherdog.com|date=2015-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\"mmajunkie.com\"/>\n**[[Bonus Awards|Fight of the Night]] (Two time) <small>vs. [[Karolina Kowalkiewicz]] and [[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]] </small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-201-Bonuses-Woodley-Ellenberger-K